463
00:26:43,446 --> 00:26:44,869
What'd you wish, Mary?

464
00:26:48,376 --> 00:26:50,651
Buffalo Gals, 
Can't you come out tonight?

465
00:26:50,651 --> 00:26:53,593
Can't you come out tonight?
Can't you come out tonight?

466
00:26:53,593 --> 00:26:56,535
Buffalo Gal, 
Can't you come out tonight?

467
00:26:56,535 --> 00:27:03,612
And dance by the light of the moon.

468
00:27:03,612 --> 00:27:05,464
What'd you wish 
when you threw that rock?

469
00:27:05,464 --> 00:27:07,293
- Oh, no.
- Come on, tell me.

470
00:27:07,293 --> 00:27:09,243
If I told you, 
it might not come true.

471
00:27:09,243 --> 00:27:11,149
What is it you want, Mary?

472
00:27:11,149 --> 00:27:12,199
What do you want?

473
00:27:12,199 --> 00:27:13,998
You, you want the moon?!

474
00:27:13,998 --> 00:27:17,501
Just say the word and I'll throw a 
lasso around it and pull it down.

475
00:27:17,501 --> 00:27:19,914
Hey, that's a pretty good idea.

476
00:27:19,914 --> 00:27:24,804
- I'll give you the moon, Mary.
- I'll take it. Then what?

477
00:27:24,804 --> 00:27:26,519
Well then, you could swallow it,

478
00:27:26,519 --> 00:27:28,626
and it'd all dissolve, see?

479
00:27:28,626 --> 00:27:32,011
And the moon beams'd shoot out 
of your fingers and your toes ...

480
00:27:32,011 --> 00:27:33,965
and the ends of your hair.

481
00:27:35,602 --> 00:27:36,957
Am I talking too much?

482
00:27:36,957 --> 00:27:38,240
Yes!

483
00:27:39,326 --> 00:27:41,539
Why don't you kiss her 
instead of talking her to death?

484
00:27:41,539 --> 00:27:42,605
How's that?

485
00:27:42,605 --> 00:27:45,642
Why don't you kiss her 
instead of talking her to death?

486
00:27:47,887 --> 00:27:49,122
Want me to kiss her, huh?

487
00:27:49,122 --> 00:27:53,915
Aw, youth is wasted 
on the wrong people!

488
00:27:53,915 --> 00:27:57,278
Hey, hey, hold on. 
Hey, mister, come on back out here.

489
00:27:57,278 --> 00:28:00,055
I'll show you some kissing 
that'll put hair back on your head.

490
00:28:00,055 --> 00:28:01,384
What are you ...

491
00:28:09,051 --> 00:28:10,219
Mary?

492
00:28:21,214 --> 00:28:23,492
Okay, I give up. Where are you?

493
00:28:23,492 --> 00:28:26,702
Over here, in the hydrangea bushes.

494
00:28:28,024 --> 00:28:30,170
Here you are. Catch.

495
00:28:30,170 --> 00:28:32,860
Wait a minute. What am I doing?

496
00:28:36,825 --> 00:28:39,390
This is a very interesting situation!

497
00:28:39,390 --> 00:28:43,046
- Please give me my robe.
- Hmm.

498
00:28:43,046 --> 00:28:45,788
A man doesn't get in a situation 
like this every day.

499
00:28:45,788 --> 00:28:47,827
I'd like to have my robe.

500
00:28:47,827 --> 00:28:49,489
Not in Bedford Falls anyway.

501
00:28:49,489 --> 00:28:52,610
- Ooooouch! Oh!
- Gesundheit.

502
00:28:52,610 --> 00:28:54,596
- George Bailey!
- This requires a little thought here.

503
00:28:54,596 --> 00:28:56,378
Give me my robe!

504
00:28:56,378 --> 00:28:58,724
I've read about things like this, 
but I never ...

505
00:28:58,724 --> 00:29:01,757
Shame on you! I'm going to 
tell your mother on you!

506
00:29:01,757 --> 00:29:04,955
Oh, my mother's way up on the corner over there.

507
00:29:04,955 --> 00:29:06,773
I'll call the police!

508
00:29:06,773 --> 00:29:09,321
They're way downtown. 
They'd be on my side, too.

509
00:29:09,321 --> 00:29:12,265
Then, then, 
then I'm going to scream!

510
00:29:12,265 --> 00:29:14,960
Maybe I could sell tickets.

511
00:29:14,960 --> 00:29:20,154
Let's see. No, no, the point is, 
in order to get this robe ...

512
00:29:20,154 --> 00:29:23,325
I've got it. I'll make 
a deal with you, Mary.

513
00:29:23,325 --> 00:29:25,130
George! 
George!

514
00:29:27,923 --> 00:29:30,181
George! Come on home. Quick.

515
00:29:30,181 --> 00:29:31,691
You father's had a stroke!

516
00:29:31,691 --> 00:29:32,807
What?!

517
00:29:33,238 --> 00:29:34,970
Mary! Mary, I'm sorry. 
I've got to go.

518
00:29:34,970 --> 00:29:36,069
Come on, George. Let's hurry!

519
00:29:36,069 --> 00:29:38,655
- Did you get a doctor?
- Yes. Campbell's there now.

520
00:29:49,633 --> 00:29:52,470
I think that's all we'll need you for, George, 
I know you're anxious to make a train.

521
00:29:52,470 --> 00:29:54,150
I have a taxi waiting downstairs.

522
00:29:54,150 --> 00:29:57,124
I want the Board to know that George 
gave up his trip to Europe ...

523
00:29:57,124 --> 00:30:00,407
to help straighten things out 
here these past few months.

524
00:30:00,407 --> 00:30:01,910
Good luck to you at school, George.

525
00:30:01,910 --> 00:30:04,203
- Thanks.
- Good luck! So long!

526
00:30:04,203 --> 00:30:06,773
Now we come to the real purpose 
of this meeting ...

527
00:30:06,773 --> 00:30:09,492
to appoint a successor 
to our dear friend, Peter Bailey.

528
00:30:09,492 --> 00:30:11,740
Mr. Chairman, 
I'd like to get to my real purpose.

529
00:30:11,740 --> 00:30:14,004
- Wait just a minute now.
- Wait for what?

530
00:30:14,004 --> 00:30:17,530
I claim this institution is not 
necessary to this town.

531
00:30:17,530 --> 00:30:21,811
Therefore, Mr. Chairman, I make a 
motion to dissolve this institution ...

532
00:30:21,811 --> 00:30:24,690
and turn its assets and liabilities 
over to the receiver.

533
00:30:24,690 --> 00:30:26,233
Potter, you dirty, contemptible ...

534
00:30:26,233 --> 00:30:27,461
I'll wring his neck, so help me, 
George,

535
00:30:27,461 --> 00:30:29,072
- you hear what that buzzard ...
- Mr. Chairman,

536
00:30:29,072 --> 00:30:33,533
it's too soon after Peter Bailey's death to talk 
about chloroforming the Building and Loan.

537
00:30:33,533 --> 00:30:35,833
Peter Bailey died three months ago.

538
00:30:35,833 --> 00:30:37,717
I second Mr. Potter's motion.

539
00:30:37,717 --> 00:30:41,689
Very well. In that case, I'll ask the 
two executive officers to withdraw.

540
00:30:41,689 --> 00:30:43,203
But before you go,

541
00:30:43,203 --> 00:30:46,149
I'm sure the whole Board wishes 
to express its deep sorrow ...

542
00:30:46,149 --> 00:30:48,587
- at the passing of Peter Bailey.
- Thank you very much.

543
00:30:48,587 --> 00:30:52,263
It was his faith and devotion that are 
responsible for this organization.

544
00:30:52,263 --> 00:30:54,258
I'll go further than that.

545
00:30:54,258 --> 00:30:58,869
I'll say that to the public, Peter 
Bailey was the Building and Loan.

546
00:30:58,869 --> 00:31:01,159
Oh, that's fine, 
Potter, coming from you,

547
00:31:01,159 --> 00:31:03,151
considering that you probably 
drove him to his grave.

548
00:31:03,151 --> 00:31:06,188
Peter Bailey was not a business man.

549
00:31:06,188 --> 00:31:10,654
That's what killed him. Oh, I don't mean 
any disrespect to him, God rest his soul.

550
00:31:10,654 --> 00:31:14,500
He was a man of 
high ideals, so-called.

551
00:31:14,500 --> 00:31:18,976
But ideals without common sense 
can ruin this town.

552
00:31:18,976 --> 00:31:22,446
Now, you take this loan here 
to Ernie Bishop ...

553
00:31:22,446 --> 00:31:28,407
you know, that fellow that sits around 
all day on his brains in his taxi, you know.

554
00:31:28,407 --> 00:31:33,855
I happen to know the bank turned down 
this loan, but he comes here ...

555
00:31:33,855 --> 00:31:39,536
and we're building him a house 
worth five thousand dollars.

556
00:31:39,536 --> 00:31:41,948
- Why?
- Well, I handled that, Mr. Potter.

557
00:31:41,948 --> 00:31:43,255
You have all the papers there.

558
00:31:43,255 --> 00:31:46,249
His salary, insurance. I can 
personally vouch for his character.

559
00:31:46,249 --> 00:31:48,915
- A friend of yours.
- Yes, sir.

560
00:31:48,915 --> 00:31:52,472
You see, if you shoot pool with 
some employee here,

561
00:31:52,472 --> 00:31:55,131
you can come and borrow money.

562
00:31:55,131 --> 00:31:56,927
What does that get us?

563
00:31:56,927 --> 00:32:02,157
A discontented, lazy rabble 
instead of a thrifty working class.

564
00:32:02,157 --> 00:32:07,369
And all because a few starry-eyed 
dreamers like Peter Bailey ...

565
00:32:07,369 --> 00:32:11,572
stir them up and fill their heads 
with a lot of impossible ideas.

566
00:32:11,572 --> 00:32:14,110
- Now, I say ...
- Just a minute. Just a ...

567
00:32:14,110 --> 00:32:16,541
Just a minute. 
Now, hold on, Mr. Potter.

568
00:32:16,541 --> 00:32:19,772
You're right when you say my father 
was no business man. I know that.

569
00:32:19,772 --> 00:32:23,087
Why he ever started this cheap penny-ante 
Building and Loan, I'll never know.

570
00:32:23,087 --> 00:32:26,476
But neither you nor anybody else can say 
anything against his character,

571
00:32:26,476 --> 00:32:28,462
because his whole life was ...

572
00:32:28,462 --> 00:32:31,159
Why, in the twenty-five years since 
he and Uncle Billy started this thing,

573
00:32:31,159 --> 00:32:33,441
he never once thought of himself. 
Isn't that right, Uncle Billy?

574
00:32:33,441 --> 00:32:36,495
He didn't save enough money to 
send Harry to school, let alone me.

575
00:32:36,495 --> 00:32:39,294
But he did help a few people 
get out of your slums, Mr. Potter.

576
00:32:39,294 --> 00:32:40,598
And what's wrong with that?

577
00:32:40,598 --> 00:32:43,313
Why ... here, 
you are all businessmen here.

578
00:32:43,313 --> 00:32:46,451
Doesn't it make them better citizens? 
Doesn't it make them better customers?

579
00:32:46,451 --> 00:32:48,520
You — you said that uh ...
what'd you say just a minute ago ...

580
00:32:48,520 --> 00:32:52,441
They, they had to wait and save their money 
before they even thought of a decent home.

581
00:32:52,441 --> 00:32:54,373
Wait! Wait for what?

582
00:32:54,373 --> 00:32:55,862
Until their children grow up 
and leave them?

583
00:32:55,862 --> 00:32:58,312
Until they're so old 
and broken-down that they ...

584
00:32:58,312 --> 00:33:01,043
Do you know how long it takes a working 
man to save five thousand dollars?

585
00:33:01,043 --> 00:33:04,505
Just remember this, Mr. Potter, 
that this rabble you're talking about ...

586
00:33:04,505 --> 00:33:08,580
they do most of the working and paying 
and living and dying in this community.

587
00:33:08,580 --> 00:33:10,843
Well, it is too much to have them 
work and pay and live and die ...

588
00:33:10,843 --> 00:33:12,876
in a couple of decent rooms 
and a bath?

589
00:33:12,876 --> 00:33:15,742
Anyway, my father didn't think so.

590
00:33:15,742 --> 00:33:17,232
People were human beings to him,

591
00:33:17,232 --> 00:33:21,137
but to you, a warped, 
frustrated old man, they're cattle.

592
00:33:21,137 --> 00:33:23,644
Well, in my book, he died a much 
richer man than you'll ever be.

593
00:33:23,644 --> 00:33:28,008
I'm not interested in your book. 
I'm talking about the Building and Loan.

594
00:33:28,008 --> 00:33:29,869
I know very well 
what you're talking about.

595
00:33:29,869 --> 00:33:33,181
You're talking about something you can't 
get your fingers on, and it's galling you.

596
00:33:33,181 --> 00:33:35,639
That's what you're 
talking about, I know.

597
00:33:35,639 --> 00:33:37,469
Well, I, I, I've said too much.

598
00:33:37,469 --> 00:33:41,140
I ... You're, you're the Board here. 
You do what you want with this thing.

599
00:33:41,140 --> 00:33:42,631
There's j-just one thing more though.

600
00:33:42,631 --> 00:33:45,795
This town needs this measly 
one-horse institution ...

601
00:33:45,795 --> 00:33:49,740
if only to have some place where people 
can come without crawling to Potter.

602
00:33:49,740 --> 00:33:51,007
Come on, Uncle Billy.

603
00:33:56,564 --> 00:34:02,099
Sentimental hogwash. 
I want my motion.

604
00:34:02,099 --> 00:34:04,372
Oh boy, that was telling him, 
George, old boy.

605
00:34:04,372 --> 00:34:06,507
You shut his big mouth. 
You should have heard him.

606
00:34:06,507 --> 00:34:07,710
What happened? 
We heard a lot of yelling.

607
00:34:07,710 --> 00:34:11,156
Well, we're being voted out of 
business after twenty-five years.

608
00:34:11,156 --> 00:34:12,626
Easy come, easy go.

609
00:34:12,626 --> 00:34:14,579
Here it is. 
"Help wanted — Female."

610
00:34:14,579 --> 00:34:16,737
You still want me 
hang around, George?

611
00:34:16,737 --> 00:34:17,919
Yeah, I'll be right down.

612
00:34:17,919 --> 00:34:19,182
Hey, you'll miss your train.

613
00:34:19,182 --> 00:34:21,046
You're a week late for 
school already. Go on.

614
00:34:21,046 --> 00:34:23,984
- What's going on in there?
- Oh, never mind. Don't worry about that.

615
00:34:23,984 --> 00:34:26,113
They're putting us out of business. 
So what?

616
00:34:26,113 --> 00:34:28,294
I can get another job. 
I'm only fifty-five.

617
00:34:28,294 --> 00:34:29,992
- Fifty-six.
- Go on, go on.

618
00:34:29,992 --> 00:34:33,216
Hey, look, you gave up your boat trip, now 
you don't want to miss college, too, do you?

619
00:34:33,216 --> 00:34:34,415
George! 
George!

620
00:34:34,415 --> 00:34:36,846
They voted Potter down. 
They want to keep it going.

621
00:34:38,299 --> 00:34:40,121
- Whoopee!
- You did it, George, you did it.

622
00:34:40,121 --> 00:34:42,276
But they got one condition, 
only one condition.

623
00:34:42,276 --> 00:34:43,994
- What's that?
- That's the best part of it.

624
00:34:43,994 --> 00:34:47,405
They've appointed George here as Executive 
Secretary to take his father's place.

625
00:34:47,405 --> 00:34:48,677
Oh, no! But, Uncle Billy ...

626
00:34:48,677 --> 00:34:50,439
You can keep him on. 
That's all right.

627
00:34:50,439 --> 00:34:52,403
As Secretary you can 
hire anyone you like.

628
00:34:52,403 --> 00:34:54,315
Dr. Campbell, now let's 
get this thing straight.

629
00:34:54,315 --> 00:34:55,872
I'm leaving. 
I'm leaving right now.

630
00:34:55,872 --> 00:34:57,598
I'm going to school. 
This is my last chance.

631
00:34:57,598 --> 00:34:59,139
Uncle Billy here, he's your man.

632
00:34:59,139 --> 00:35:01,767
But, George, they'll vote 
with Potter otherwise.

633
00:35:04,142 --> 00:35:06,515
I know, I know, he didn't go.

634
00:35:06,515 --> 00:35:07,596
That's right.

635
00:35:07,596 --> 00:35:12,205
Not only that, but he gave his school money 
to his brother, Harry, and sent him to college.

636
00:35:12,205 --> 00:35:13,999
Harry became a football star.

637
00:35:13,999 --> 00:35:15,777
Made second team All-American.

638
00:35:15,777 --> 00:35:18,339
Yeah, but what happened to George?

639
00:35:18,339 --> 00:35:21,477
George got four years older, 
waiting for Harry to come back ...

640
00:35:21,477 --> 00:35:23,256
and take over the Building and Loan.

641
00:35:23,256 --> 00:35:25,952
Oh, there are plenty of jobs around 
for somebody that likes to travel.

642
00:35:25,952 --> 00:35:27,143
Look at this. There ...

643
00:35:27,143 --> 00:35:31,610
Venezuela oil fields — Wanted. 
Man with construction experience.

644
00:35:31,610 --> 00:35:36,365
Here's the Yukon, oh, right here — 
wanted - man with engineering experience.

645
00:35:37,226 --> 00:35:39,073
There she blows.

646
00:35:39,073 --> 00:35:41,464
You know what the three most exciting 
sounds in the world are?

647
00:35:41,464 --> 00:35:43,880
- Uh-huh. 
- Breakfast is served, lunch is served, dinner ...

648
00:35:43,880 --> 00:35:45,501
No, no, no, no!

649
00:35:45,501 --> 00:35:49,088
- Anchor chains, plane motors, and train whistles.
- Peanut?

650
00:35:49,088 --> 00:35:50,409
There's the Professor now.

651
00:35:50,409 --> 00:35:54,321
- Old Professor Phil Beta Kappa Bailey! All-American.
- Well, if it isn't old George Geographic Explorer Bailey.

652
00:35:54,321 --> 00:35:56,172
What? No husky dogs? No sled?

653
00:35:56,172 --> 00:35:57,642
Uncle Billy, you haven't changed a bit.

654
00:35:57,642 --> 00:36:01,032
- Nobody ever changes here, you know that.
- Oh, am I glad to see you.

655
00:36:01,032 --> 00:36:03,305
- Say, where's mother?
- She's home, cooking the fatted calf.

656
00:36:03,305 --> 00:36:05,284
- Come on. Let's go.
- Oh, wait! Wait, wait, wait, wait a minute.

657
00:36:05,284 --> 00:36:08,277
George, Uncle Billy, 
I want you to meet Ruth.

658
00:36:08,277 --> 00:36:09,628
- Hello.
- How do you do.

659
00:36:09,628 --> 00:36:12,456
- Ruth Dakin.
- Ruth Dakin Bailey, if you don't mind.

660
00:36:12,456 --> 00:36:13,548
Huh?

661
00:36:13,548 --> 00:36:17,062
Well, I wired you I had a surprise. 
Here she is. Meet the wife.

662
00:36:17,062 --> 00:36:19,955
Well, what do you know — wife.

663
00:36:21,002 --> 00:36:23,826
Well, how do you do. 
Congratulations.

664
00:36:23,826 --> 00:36:25,874
What am I doing? Congratulations!

665
00:36:25,874 --> 00:36:29,760
They're married ...
why didn't you tell somebody?

666
00:36:29,760 --> 00:36:33,237
... Oh, I can't wait 
to see Tilly's face.

667
00:36:33,237 --> 00:36:34,646
- Did you really marry him?
- Why, yes ...

668
00:36:34,646 --> 00:36:37,971
What's a pretty girl like you doing 
marrying this two-headed brother of mine?

669
00:36:37,971 --> 00:36:39,619
Well, I tell you. 
It's purely mercenary.

670
00:36:39,619 --> 00:36:40,905
My father offered him a job.

671
00:36:40,905 --> 00:36:45,560
Oh, he gets you and a job? 
Well, Harry's cup runneth over.

672
00:36:45,560 --> 00:36:48,460
Uh, George, about that job, 
Ruth spoke out of turn.

673
00:36:48,460 --> 00:36:50,229
I never said I'd take it.

674
00:36:50,229 --> 00:36:53,098
You've been holding the bag here 
for four years, and ...

675
00:36:53,098 --> 00:36:54,740
well, I won't let you down, George.

676
00:36:54,740 --> 00:36:57,010
I would like to ... Oh, wait a minute. 
I forgot the bags.

677
00:36:57,010 --> 00:36:58,105
I'll be right back.

678
00:36:58,995 --> 00:37:03,736
It was a surprise to me. This is the 
new Mrs. Bailey, my nephew's wife.

679
00:37:03,736 --> 00:37:09,535
Old, old friends of the family.

680
00:37:09,535 --> 00:37:12,639
- Oh, of course, I've heard him speak of you.
- And I want you to tell you,

681
00:37:12,639 --> 00:37:19,203
we're going to give the biggest 
party this town ever saw.

682
00:37:19,203 --> 00:37:21,104
Here, have some popcorn.

683
00:37:22,459 --> 00:37:24,934
George, George, George, 
that's all Harry ever talks about.

684
00:37:24,934 --> 00:37:29,095
Uh, uh, uh, Ruth, uh, this, 
uh, what about this job?

685
00:37:29,095 --> 00:37:31,590
Oh, well, my father owns 
a glass factory in Buffalo.

686
00:37:31,590 --> 00:37:34,050
He wants to get Harry started 
in the research business.

687
00:37:34,050 --> 00:37:36,621
- Well, is it a good job?
- Oh, yes, very.

