00:52:19,335 --> 00:52:20,686
I'll be back in a minute, Mary.

921
00:52:37,900 --> 00:52:40,494
Well, hello, everybody. 
Mrs. Thompson, how are you?

922
00:52:40,494 --> 00:52:42,856
Charlie? 
What's the matter here, can't you get in?

923
00:53:00,662 --> 00:53:02,779
What is this, Uncle Billy? 
A holiday?

924
00:53:03,400 --> 00:53:04,463
George ...

925
00:53:05,204 --> 00:53:06,656
Come on in, everybody. 
That's right.

926
00:53:07,687 --> 00:53:08,982
Just come on in.

927
00:53:12,836 --> 00:53:14,444
Now look, 
why don't you all sit down?

928
00:53:14,444 --> 00:53:16,251
There are a lot of seats over there.

929
00:53:17,691 --> 00:53:19,110
Just make yourself at home.

930
00:53:21,145 --> 00:53:23,262
George, can I see you a minute?

931
00:53:24,309 --> 00:53:26,360
- Why didn't you call me?
- I just did, but they said you left.

932
00:53:26,360 --> 00:53:28,019
This is a pickle, George. 
This is a pickle.

933
00:53:28,019 --> 00:53:29,504
All right now, what happened? 
How did it start?

934
00:53:29,504 --> 00:53:32,048
Well, how does a thing like this ever start? 
All I know is the bank called our loan.

935
00:53:32,048 --> 00:53:33,378
- When?
- About an hour ago.

936
00:53:33,378 --> 00:53:35,409
- I had to hand over all our cash.
- All of it?

937
00:53:35,409 --> 00:53:37,088
Every cent of it 
and it still was less than we owe.

938
00:53:37,088 --> 00:53:38,919
Holy mackerel!

939
00:53:38,919 --> 00:53:42,718
And then I got scared, George, 
and closed the doors. I — I — I ...

940
00:53:44,959 --> 00:53:46,584
The whole town's gone crazy.

941
00:53:46,584 --> 00:53:48,124
Yes, h-hello?

942
00:53:48,124 --> 00:53:50,291
George, it's Potter.

943
00:53:54,078 --> 00:53:55,634
- Hello?
- George,

944
00:53:55,634 --> 00:54:01,127
there is a rumor around town that you've 
closed your doors. Is that true?

945
00:54:01,127 --> 00:54:05,246
Oh, well, I'm very glad to hear that. 
George, are you all right?

946
00:54:05,246 --> 00:54:08,363
- Do you need any police?
- Police? What's for?

947
00:54:08,363 --> 00:54:12,627
Well, mobs get pretty ugly 
sometimes, you know.

948
00:54:12,627 --> 00:54:17,468
George, I'm going all out 
to help in this crisis.

949
00:54:17,468 --> 00:54:22,919
I've just guaranteed the bank 
sufficient funds to meet their needs.

950
00:54:22,919 --> 00:54:26,223
They'll close up for a week 
and then reopen.

951
00:54:27,016 --> 00:54:28,315
He just took over the bank.

952
00:54:29,158 --> 00:54:34,745
I may lose a fortune, but I'm 
willing to guarantee your people too.

953
00:54:34,745 --> 00:54:39,923
Just tell them to bring their shares over here, 
and I will pay fifty cents on the dollar.

954
00:54:39,923 --> 00:54:42,178
Aw, you never miss a trick, 
do you, Potter?

955
00:54:42,178 --> 00:54:43,292
Well, you're gonna miss this one.

956
00:54:43,292 --> 00:54:47,242
If you close your doors before 
six P.M., you will never reopen.

957
00:54:55,980 --> 00:54:59,150
George, was it a nice wedding? 
Gosh, I wanted to be there.

958
00:55:00,011 --> 00:55:01,124
Yeah ...

959
00:55:02,988 --> 00:55:04,983
You can take this one off now.

960
00:55:13,703 --> 00:55:19,159
Now, just remember that this thing 
isn't as black as it appears.

961
00:55:28,712 --> 00:55:30,525
I have some news for you folks.

962
00:55:30,525 --> 00:55:33,816
I was just talking to old man Potter and 
he's guaranteed cash payments at the bank.

963
00:55:33,816 --> 00:55:35,439
The bank's going to reopen next week.

964
00:55:35,439 --> 00:55:37,354
But, George, I got my money here.

965
00:55:37,354 --> 00:55:39,148
Did he guarantee this place?

966
00:55:39,148 --> 00:55:40,935
Well, no, Charlie. 
I didn't even ask him.

967
00:55:40,935 --> 00:55:43,611
- We don't need Potter over here.
- I'll take mine now.

968
00:55:44,318 --> 00:55:48,826
No, but you — you ... you're 
thinking of this place all wrong.

969
00:55:48,826 --> 00:55:50,674
As if I had the money back in a safe.

970
00:55:50,674 --> 00:55:52,741
The, the money's not here.

971
00:55:52,741 --> 00:55:55,267
Well, your money's in Joe's house ...
that's right next to yours.

972
00:55:55,267 --> 00:55:59,238
And in the Kennedy House, and Mrs. Macklin's 
house, and, and a hundred others.

973
00:55:59,238 --> 00:56:01,078
Why, you're lending them 
the money to build,

974
00:56:01,078 --> 00:56:02,809
and then, they're going to pay it 
back to you as best they can.

975
00:56:02,809 --> 00:56:04,604
Now what are you going to do? 
Foreclose on them?

976
00:56:04,604 --> 00:56:07,447
I got two hundred and 
forty-two dollars in here ...

977
00:56:07,447 --> 00:56:10,907
and two hundred and forty-two dollars 
isn't going to break anybody.

978
00:56:11,800 --> 00:56:15,688
Okay, Tom. All right. 
Here you are. You sign this.

979
00:56:15,688 --> 00:56:18,316
- You'll get your money in sixty days.
- Sixty days?

980
00:56:18,316 --> 00:56:20,488
Well, now that's what you agreed 
to when you bought you shares.

981
00:56:20,488 --> 00:56:22,613
- Tom ...Tom ... Did you get your money?
- No.

982
00:56:22,613 --> 00:56:26,424
Well, I did. Old man Potter'll pay fifty cents 
on the dollar for every share you got.

983
00:56:26,424 --> 00:56:29,168
- Fifty cents on the dollar!
- Yes, cash!

984
00:56:29,168 --> 00:56:31,844
- Well, what do you say?
- Now, Tom,

985
00:56:31,844 --> 00:56:33,557
you have to stick to your original agreement.

986
00:56:33,557 --> 00:56:36,081
- Now give us sixty days on this.
- Okay, Randall.

987
00:56:36,081 --> 00:56:38,918
- Are you going to go to Potter's?
- Better get half than nothing.

988
00:56:39,325 --> 00:56:41,923
Tom! Tom!

989
00:56:41,923 --> 00:56:44,167
Randall, now wait a minute, wait ...

990
00:56:44,167 --> 00:56:45,979
now listen ... now listen to me.

991
00:56:45,979 --> 00:56:48,369
I — I beg of you not to do this thing.

992
00:56:48,369 --> 00:56:50,093
If Potter gets ahold 
of this Building and Loan,

993
00:56:50,093 --> 00:56:52,069
there'll never be another decent 
house built in this town.

994
00:56:52,069 --> 00:56:54,661
He's already got charge of the bank. 
He's got the bus line.

995
00:56:54,661 --> 00:56:56,948
He's got the department stores. 
And now he's after us.

996
00:56:56,948 --> 00:56:58,539
Why? Well, it's very simple.

997
00:56:58,539 --> 00:57:01,081
Because we're cutting in on 
his business, that's why.

998
00:57:01,081 --> 00:57:03,125
And because he wants to keep 
you living in his slums ...

999
00:57:03,125 --> 00:57:05,205
and paying the kind of rent he decides.

1000
00:57:05,205 --> 00:57:08,019
Joe, you had one of those Potter houses, 
didn't you? Well, have you forgotten?

1001
00:57:08,019 --> 00:57:10,852
Have you forgotten what he charged 
for that broken-down shack?

1002
00:57:10,852 --> 00:57:13,855
Here, Ed. You know, you remember last 
year when things weren't going so well,

1003
00:57:13,855 --> 00:57:15,173
you couldn't make your payments.

1004
00:57:15,173 --> 00:57:18,276
You didn't lose your house, did you? 
Do you think Potter would have let you keep it?

1005
00:57:18,276 --> 00:57:21,346
Ca-Can't you understand 
what's happening here?

1006
00:57:21,346 --> 00:57:23,061
Don't you see what's happening?

1007
00:57:23,061 --> 00:57:25,229
Potter isn't selling. 
Potter's buying.

1008
00:57:25,229 --> 00:57:28,165
And why? Because we're panicky 
and he's not. That's why.

1009
00:57:28,165 --> 00:57:29,311
He's picking up some bargains.

1010
00:57:29,311 --> 00:57:31,942
Now, We-We can get 
through this thing all right.

1011
00:57:31,942 --> 00:57:35,301
We — We've got to stick together, though. 
We've got to have faith in each other.

1012
00:57:35,301 --> 00:57:38,508
But my husband hasn't worked in 
over a year and I need money.

1013
00:57:38,508 --> 00:57:41,876
- How am I going to live until the bank opens?
- I got doctor bills to pay.

1014
00:57:41,876 --> 00:57:44,517
- I need cash.
- I can't feed my kids on faith.

1015
00:57:44,517 --> 00:57:46,608
How much do you need?

1016
00:57:46,608 --> 00:57:49,928
Hey! I got two thousand dollars.

1017
00:57:50,824 --> 00:57:53,403
Here's two thousand dollars. This'll 
tide us over until the bank reopens.

1018
00:57:53,403 --> 00:57:54,483
All right, 
Tom, how much do you need?

1019
00:57:54,483 --> 00:57:56,108
Two hundred and forty-two dollars.

1020
00:57:56,108 --> 00:57:58,530
Aw, Tom, just enough to tide you over 
till the bank reopens.

1021
00:57:58,530 --> 00:58:01,252
I'll take 
two hundred and forty-two dollars.

1022
00:58:03,661 --> 00:58:05,472
- There you are.
- That'll close my account.

1023
00:58:05,472 --> 00:58:07,922
Your account's still here. 
That's a loan.

1024
00:58:07,922 --> 00:58:09,667
Okay. All right, Ed?

1025
00:58:09,667 --> 00:58:12,010
- I got 300 dollars here, George.
- Alright, now, Ed ...

1026
00:58:12,010 --> 00:58:15,046
wh-wh-what'll it take till the 
bank opens? What do you need?

1027
00:58:15,046 --> 00:58:19,301
- Well, I — I suppose twenty dollars.
- Twenty dollars. Now you're talking.

1028
00:58:19,301 --> 00:58:20,499
Fine. Thanks, Ed.

1029
00:58:20,499 --> 00:58:22,123
All right now, Mrs. Thompson, 
how much do you want?

1030
00:58:22,123 --> 00:58:24,019
- But it's your own money, George.
- Never mind about that.

1031
00:58:24,019 --> 00:58:26,426
- How much do you want?
- I can get along with twenty, all right.

1032
00:58:26,426 --> 00:58:28,436
- Twenty dollars.
- And I'll sign a paper.

1033
00:58:28,436 --> 00:58:29,568
You don't have to sign anything.

1034
00:58:29,568 --> 00:58:31,090
I know you — you'll pay it when you can.

1035
00:58:31,090 --> 00:58:33,326
That's okay. All right, Mrs. Davis?

1036
00:58:33,326 --> 00:58:37,451
- Could I have 17.50?
- Seven ...

1037
00:58:37,451 --> 00:58:40,502
Bless your heart, of course you 
can have it. You got fifty cents?

1038
00:58:40,502 --> 00:58:41,948
- Seven ...
- We're going to make it, George.

1039
00:58:41,948 --> 00:58:45,780
- They'll never close us up today!
- Six, five, four,

1040
00:58:45,780 --> 00:58:49,064
three, two, one ...

1041
00:58:49,064 --> 00:58:50,418
Bingo!

1042
00:58:50,418 --> 00:58:52,640
We made it. Close the door, Ernie. 
We made it. Look.

1043
00:58:52,640 --> 00:58:55,148
Look, we're still in business. 
We're still got two bucks left.

1044
00:58:55,148 --> 00:58:56,890
Well, look, let's have some of that. 
Let's celebrate, huh.

1045
00:58:56,890 --> 00:58:58,491
G-Get some glasses, Tilly.

1046
00:58:58,491 --> 00:59:00,353
Well, a couple of financial wizards.

1047
00:59:00,353 --> 00:59:02,007
Those Rockefellers.

1048
00:59:02,007 --> 00:59:04,413
Get a tray for these two great 
big important simoleans here.

1049
00:59:04,413 --> 00:59:06,072
We'll save them for seed. 
A toast.

1050
00:59:06,072 --> 00:59:09,493
A toast! A toast to Mama Dollar 
and to Papa Dollar,

1051
00:59:09,493 --> 00:59:11,751
and if you want to keep this 
old Building and Loan in business,

1052
00:59:11,751 --> 00:59:14,098
- you better have a family real quick.
- I wish they were rabbits.

1053
00:59:14,098 --> 00:59:15,424
I wish they were, too.

1054
00:59:16,568 --> 00:59:18,930
Okay, let's put them in safe 
and see what happens.

1055
00:59:28,223 --> 00:59:31,733
- Folks, folks, wedding cigars!
- Oh-oh ... wedding!

1056
00:59:31,733 --> 00:59:35,322
Holy mackerel, I'm married! 
Where's Mary? Mary ...

1057
00:59:35,322 --> 00:59:36,399
Well, poor Mary.

1058
00:59:36,399 --> 00:59:38,483
Look, I've got a train to catch. 
Well, the train's gone.

1059
00:59:38,483 --> 00:59:41,110
I wonder if Ernie's still 
here with his taxicab?

1060
00:59:41,110 --> 00:59:43,567
George, there's a call for you.

1061
00:59:43,567 --> 00:59:46,390
Look, will you get my wife on the phone? 
She's probably over at her mother's.

1062
00:59:46,390 --> 00:59:48,963
- Mrs. Bailey is on the phone.
- I don't want Mrs. Bailey.

1063
00:59:48,963 --> 00:59:52,133
I want my wife. Mrs. Bailey! 
Mrs ... oh, that's my wife.

1064
00:59:52,133 --> 00:59:54,158
Here, I'll take it in here.

1065
00:59:54,158 --> 00:59:57,687
Mary! Hello. Listen, dear. 
I'm sorry ...

1066
00:59:57,687 --> 01:00:02,135
What? Come home? What home?

1067
01:00:02,135 --> 01:00:04,341
Three-twenty Sycamore? 
Well, what ...

1068
01:00:04,341 --> 01:00:09,315
whose home is that? 
The Waldorf Hotel, huh?

1069
01:00:19,487 --> 01:00:22,317
Hey, this is the company's posters, 
and the company won't like this.

1070
01:00:22,317 --> 01:00:24,514
How would you like to get 
a ticket next week?

1071
01:00:24,514 --> 01:00:27,447
- Haven't you any romance in you?
- Sure I have, but I got rid of it.

1072
01:00:27,447 --> 01:00:28,595
Liver pills!

1073
01:00:28,595 --> 01:00:31,424
Who wants to see 
liver pills on their honeymoon?

1074
01:00:31,424 --> 01:00:35,397
What we want is romantic places, beautiful 
places ... places George wants to go.

1075
01:00:36,887 --> 01:00:39,997
- Hey, Bert. Here he comes.
- Come on, we got to get this up. He's coming.

1076
01:00:39,997 --> 01:00:41,922
- Who?
- The groom, idiot.

1077
01:00:41,922 --> 01:00:43,869
This is their honeymoon. 
Come on. Get that ladder.

1078
01:00:43,869 --> 01:00:45,193
What are they — ducks?

1079
01:00:48,315 --> 01:00:50,749
- Get that ladder up here.
- All right, all right.

1080
01:00:50,749 --> 01:00:53,151
- Hurry up. Hurry up. Hurry up.
- I'm hurrying.

1081
01:01:02,583 --> 01:01:05,211
Hiya ... Geo ... 
uh ... good evening, sir.

1082
01:01:07,381 --> 01:01:09,229
Entree, Monsieur.

1083
01:01:10,804 --> 01:01:18,126
- Entree.
♪ Islands of Hawaii ♪

1084
01:01:18,126 --> 01:01:27,935
♪ Where skies of blue are calling me ♪

1085
01:01:27,935 --> 01:01:37,827
♪ Where balmy air and golden moonlight, ♪

1086
01:01:37,827 --> 01:01:47,118
♪ caress The waving palms of Waikiki ♪

1087
01:02:30,677 --> 01:02:32,642
Welcome home, Mr. Bailey.

1088
01:02:38,082 --> 01:02:40,098
Well, I'll be ...

1089
01:02:44,988 --> 01:02:47,410
Mary, where did you ...

1090
01:02:53,913 --> 01:02:59,564
♪ I Love You Truly, ♪

1091
01:02:59,564 --> 01:03:04,685
♪ Truly, Dear. ♪

1092
01:03:04,685 --> 01:03:09,226
♪ Life with Its Shadows, ♪

1093
01:03:09,226 --> 01:03:10,313
Oh, Mary ...

1094
01:03:10,313 --> 01:03:13,148
♪ Life with Its Tears. ♪

1095
01:03:13,148 --> 01:03:14,903
Remember the night we broke 
the windows in this old house?

1096
01:03:14,903 --> 01:03:20,332
♪ Fade into Dreams, ♪
- This is what I wished for.

1097
01:03:20,332 --> 01:03:24,360
♪ When I Feel You Are Near, ♪

1098
01:03:24,360 --> 01:03:34,043
- Darling, you're wonderful.
♪ I Love You Truly, ♪

1099
01:03:34,043 --> 01:03:41,110
♪ Truly, Dear. ♪

1100
01:03:49,497 --> 01:03:53,696
- Martini, you rented a new house?
- Rent?

1101
01:03:54,912 --> 01:03:57,440
- You hear what he say, Mr. Bailey?
- What's that?

1102
01:03:57,440 --> 01:03:59,406
I own the house.

1103
01:03:59,406 --> 01:04:02,835
Me, Giuseppe Martini, 
I own my own house.

1104
01:04:02,835 --> 01:04:06,248
No more we live like pigs 
in this Potter's Field.

1105
01:04:06,248 --> 01:04:07,698
Hurry, Marie!

1106
01:04:07,698 --> 01:04:09,121
Come on ... Bring the baby.

1107
01:04:09,977 --> 01:04:11,878
This is like a dream!

1108
01:04:11,878 --> 01:04:13,076
I'll take the kids in the car.

1109
01:04:13,076 --> 01:04:14,998
Oh, thank you, Mr. Bailey.

1110
01:04:14,998 --> 01:04:17,032
All right, kids. Here.

1111
01:04:17,032 --> 01:04:18,129
Get in here.

1112
01:04:18,129 --> 01:04:20,062
Now get right up on the seat there.

1113
01:04:22,305 --> 01:04:24,185
Get the ... get the dog!

1114
01:04:26,238 --> 01:04:27,997
You've got a goat too!

1115
01:04:29,316 --> 01:04:35,003
- All right. Goodbye.
- Goodbye, everybody!

1116
01:04:37,683 --> 01:04:38,712
All in.

1117
01:04:57,471 --> 01:04:59,587
Mr. and Mrs. Martini, welcome home.

1118
01:05:00,377 --> 01:05:02,678
Good old George. 
He's always making a speech.

1119
01:05:03,947 --> 01:05:05,780
Hee-haw!

1120
01:05:05,780 --> 01:05:09,777
- Sam Wainwright!
- Oh, who cares!

1121
01:05:09,777 --> 01:05:12,817
Bread! That this house 
may never know hunger.

1122
01:05:13,594 --> 01:05:17,091
Salt! That life may 
always have flavor!

1123
01:05:17,091 --> 01:05:20,875
And wine!! That joy and 
prosperity may reign forever.

1124
01:05:20,875 --> 01:05:22,809
Enter the Martini castle!

1125
01:05:24,537 --> 01:05:26,944
Look, Mr. Potter, 
it's no skin off my nose.

1126
01:05:26,944 --> 01:05:28,808
I'm just your little rent collector.

1127
01:05:28,808 --> 01:05:32,637
But you can't laugh off this 
Bailey Park anymore. Look at it.

1128
01:05:33,941 --> 01:05:35,733
Congressman Black is here to see you.

1129
01:05:35,733 --> 01:05:38,890
Oh, tell the congressman to wait.
Go on.

1130
01:05:38,890 --> 01:05:41,773
Fifteen years ago, a half-dozen 
houses stuck here and there.

1131
01:05:41,773 --> 01:05:44,099
There's the old cemetery, squirrels, 
buttercups, daisies.

1132
01:05:44,099 --> 01:05:45,905
I used to hunt rabbits there myself.

1133
01:05:47,312 --> 01:05:48,716
Look at it today.

1134
01:05:48,716 --> 01:05:51,720
Dozens of the prettiest 
little homes you ever saw.

1135
01:05:51,720 --> 01:05:54,993
Ninety per cent owned by suckers 
who used to pay rent to you!

1136
01:05:54,993 --> 01:05:58,472
Your Potter's Field, my dear 
Mr. Employer, is becoming just that.

1137
01:05:58,472 --> 01:06:02,016
And are the local yokels making with 
those David and Goliath wisecracks.

1138
01:06:02,016 --> 01:06:03,743
Oh, they are, are they?

1139
01:06:03,743 --> 01:06:06,625
Even though they know the Baileys 
never made a dime out of it.

1140
01:06:06,625 --> 01:06:07,909
You know very well why,

1141
01:06:07,909 --> 01:06:09,313
the Baileys were all chumps.

1142
01:06:09,313 --> 01:06:13,487
Every one of these homes is worth twice 
what it cost the Building and Loan to build.

