01:06:13,487 --> 01:06:16,181
- If I were you, Mr. Potter ...
- Well, you are not me.

1144
01:06:16,181 --> 01:06:19,552
As I say, it's no skin off my nose.

1145
01:06:22,829 --> 01:06:27,208
But one of these days this bright young man 
is going to be asking George Bailey for a job.

1146
01:06:29,905 --> 01:06:33,483
The Bailey family has been a boil 
on my neck long enough.

1147
01:06:33,483 --> 01:06:34,746
- Yes, sir?
- Come in here.

1148
01:06:35,451 --> 01:06:37,760
We just stopped in town to take a 
look at the new factory, and then ...

1149
01:06:37,760 --> 01:06:39,779
- we're going to drive on down to Florida.
- Oh ...

1150
01:06:39,779 --> 01:06:42,313
- Why don't you have your friends join us?
- Why, sure.

1151
01:06:42,313 --> 01:06:45,230
Hey, why don't you kids drive down 
with us, huh?

1152
01:06:45,230 --> 01:06:48,099
Oh, I'm afraid 
I couldn't get away, Sam.

1153
01:06:48,099 --> 01:06:50,165
Still got the nose 
to the old grindstone, eh?

1154
01:06:50,165 --> 01:06:55,121
Jane, I offered to let George in on the ground 
floor in plastics and he turned me down cold.

1155
01:06:55,121 --> 01:06:57,880
- Oh, now don't rub it in.
- I'm not rubbing it in.

1156
01:06:57,880 --> 01:06:59,794
Well, I guess we better run along.

1157
01:06:59,794 --> 01:07:01,337
Awfully glad to have met you, Mary.

1158
01:07:01,337 --> 01:07:02,341
- Nice meeting you.
- Goodbye.

1159
01:07:02,341 --> 01:07:03,776
- Goodbye, George.
- So long, George.

1160
01:07:03,776 --> 01:07:04,797
- See you in the funny papers.
- Goodbye, Sam.

1161
01:07:04,797 --> 01:07:07,141
- So long, Mary.
- So long, Sam. Have fun.

1162
01:07:07,141 --> 01:07:08,221
Thanks for dropping around.

1163
01:07:08,221 --> 01:07:10,019
Florida! Hee-haw!

1164
01:07:10,019 --> 01:07:11,081
Hee-haw.

1165
01:07:40,416 --> 01:07:41,465
Thank you, sir.

1166
01:07:42,071 --> 01:07:43,408
Quite a cigar, Mr. Potter.

1167
01:07:43,408 --> 01:07:45,889
You like it? I'll send you a box.

1168
01:07:54,570 --> 01:07:58,761
Well, I, uh, I suppose 
I'll find out sooner or later,

1169
01:07:58,761 --> 01:08:01,120
but just what exactly did you want 
to see me about?

1170
01:08:02,877 --> 01:08:08,048
George, now that's just 
what I like so much about you.

1171
01:08:08,048 --> 01:08:11,836
George, I'm an old man, 
and most people hate me.

1172
01:08:11,836 --> 01:08:14,840
But I don't like them, either, 
so that that makes it all even.

1173
01:08:14,840 --> 01:08:19,861
You know, just as well as I do, that I 
run practically everything in this town ...

1174
01:08:19,861 --> 01:08:22,800
but the Bailey Building and Loan.

1175
01:08:22,800 --> 01:08:27,539
You know, also, that for a number of years 
I've been trying to get control of it or kill it.

1176
01:08:27,539 --> 01:08:29,870
But I haven't been able to do it.

1177
01:08:29,870 --> 01:08:32,868
You have been stopping me.

1178
01:08:32,868 --> 01:08:36,196
In fact, you have beaten me, George,

1179
01:08:36,196 --> 01:08:41,268
and as anyone in this county 
can tell you, that takes some doing.

1180
01:08:41,268 --> 01:08:44,494
Take during the depression, 
for instance.

1181
01:08:44,494 --> 01:08:47,790
You and I were the only ones 
that kept our heads.

1182
01:08:47,790 --> 01:08:51,680
You saved the Building and Loan, 
I saved all the rest.

1183
01:08:51,680 --> 01:08:54,448
Yeah. Well, most people say 
you stole all the rest.

1184
01:08:54,448 --> 01:08:58,732
The envious ones say that, 
George, the suckers.

1185
01:08:58,732 --> 01:09:03,282
Now, I have stated 
my side very frankly.

1186
01:09:03,282 --> 01:09:06,287
Now, let's look at your side.

1187
01:09:06,287 --> 01:09:13,229
Young man, twenty-seven, twenty-eight, 
married, making say ... forty a week.

1188
01:09:13,229 --> 01:09:16,729
- Forty-five!
- Forty-five. Forty-five.

1189
01:09:16,729 --> 01:09:19,246
Out of which, after supporting 
your mother ...

1190
01:09:19,246 --> 01:09:23,883
and paying your bills, you're 
able to keep, say ten, if you skimp.

1191
01:09:23,883 --> 01:09:28,336
A child or two comes along, and you 
won't even be able to save the ten.

1192
01:09:28,336 --> 01:09:32,658
Now, if this young man of 
twenty-eight was a common,

1193
01:09:32,658 --> 01:09:35,667
ordinary yokel, 
I'd say he was doing fine.

1194
01:09:35,667 --> 01:09:39,901
But, George Bailey is not a common, 
ordinary yokel.

1195
01:09:39,901 --> 01:09:43,933
He's an intelligent, 
smart, ambitious young man,

1196
01:09:43,933 --> 01:09:49,421
who hates his job, who hates the Building 
and Loan, almost as much as I do.

1197
01:09:49,421 --> 01:09:54,359
A young man who's been dying to get 
out on his own ever since he was born.

1198
01:09:54,359 --> 01:09:57,386
A young man ... the smartest one 
of the crowd, mind you,

1199
01:09:57,386 --> 01:10:00,841
a young man who has to sit by and 
watch his friends go places,

1200
01:10:00,841 --> 01:10:02,540
because he's trapped.

1201
01:10:02,540 --> 01:10:10,459
Yes, sir, trapped into frittering his life away  
playing nursemaid to a lot of garlic-eaters.

1202
01:10:10,459 --> 01:10:13,824
Do I paint a correct picture, 
or do I exaggerate?

1203
01:10:16,099 --> 01:10:17,625
Oh, what's your point, Mr. Potter?

1204
01:10:17,625 --> 01:10:21,197
- My point? My point is, I want to hire you.
- Hire me?

1205
01:10:21,197 --> 01:10:24,937
I want you to manage my affairs, 
run my properties.

1206
01:10:24,937 --> 01:10:30,056
George, I'll start you out at 
twenty thousand dollars a year.

1208
01:10:33,967 --> 01:10:37,007
Twenty thous ...
twenty thousand dollars a year?

1209
01:10:37,007 --> 01:10:40,476
You wouldn't mind living 
in the nicest house in town,

1210
01:10:40,476 --> 01:10:43,109
buying your wife 
a lot of fine clothes,

1211
01:10:43,109 --> 01:10:47,921
a couple of business trips to New York 
a year, maybe once in a while Europe.

1212
01:10:47,921 --> 01:10:49,593
You wouldn't mind that, 
would you, George?

1213
01:10:49,593 --> 01:10:51,032
Would I?

1214
01:10:53,843 --> 01:10:56,070
Y-You're not talking to somebody 
else around here, are you?

1215
01:10:56,070 --> 01:10:58,707
you know, th-this is me, 
you remember me? George Bailey.

1216
01:10:58,707 --> 01:11:04,278
Oh, yes, George Bailey. 
Whose ship has just come in,

1217
01:11:04,278 --> 01:11:07,626
provided he has enough brains 
to climb aboard.

1218
01:11:16,003 --> 01:11:17,272
Holy mackerel!

1219
01:11:20,315 --> 01:11:22,880
Well, how about the 
Building and Loan?

1220
01:11:22,880 --> 01:11:26,522
Oh, confound it, man! 
Are you afraid of success?

1221
01:11:26,522 --> 01:11:31,569
I'm offering you a three-year contract at 
twenty thousand dollars a year, starting today.

1222
01:11:31,569 --> 01:11:33,426
Is it a deal, or isn't it?

1223
01:11:35,037 --> 01:11:36,820
Well, Mr. Potter, I ...

1224
01:11:36,820 --> 01:11:41,647
I — I know I ought to jump 
at the chance but I — I just, uh,

1225
01:11:41,647 --> 01:11:45,606
I — I wonder if-if it would be possible for you 
to give me twenty-four hours to think it over?

1226
01:11:45,606 --> 01:11:47,475
Sure, sure, sure.

1227
01:11:47,475 --> 01:11:50,209
You go on home 
and talk about it to your wife.

1228
01:11:50,209 --> 01:11:51,822
- I'd like to do that.
- Yeah.

1229
01:11:51,822 --> 01:11:54,145
In the meantime, 
I'll draw up the papers.

1230
01:11:54,145 --> 01:11:56,415
- All right, sir.
- Okay, George?

1231
01:11:57,772 --> 01:11:59,299
Okay, Mr. Potter.

1233
01:12:09,580 --> 01:12:12,512
No, no, no, no. Wait a minute here. 
Wait a minute.

1234
01:12:12,512 --> 01:12:15,607
I don't need twenty-four hours. 
I, I don't have to talk to anybody.

1235
01:12:15,607 --> 01:12:17,746
I know right now, 
and the answer is no! No!

1236
01:12:17,746 --> 01:12:19,338
Doggone it!

1237
01:12:19,338 --> 01:12:21,928
You sit around here 
and you spin your little webs ...

1238
01:12:21,928 --> 01:12:24,117
and you think the whole world revolves 
around you and your money.

1239
01:12:24,117 --> 01:12:25,983
Well, it doesn't, Mr. Potter.

1240
01:12:25,983 --> 01:12:29,205
In the ... in the whole 
vast configuration of things,

1241
01:12:29,205 --> 01:12:32,177
I'd say you were nothing 
but a scurvy little spider.

1242
01:12:32,177 --> 01:12:36,946
You ... and that goes for you, too.

1243
01:12:40,858 --> 01:12:43,234
And it goes for you, too.

1244
01:12:49,954 --> 01:12:53,469
If you wouldn't mind living 
in the nicest house in town.

1245
01:12:53,469 --> 01:12:56,358
Buying your wife 
a lot of fine clothes.

1246
01:12:56,358 --> 01:12:59,856
Going to New York on a business 
trip a couple of times a year.

1247
01:12:59,856 --> 01:13:02,421
Maybe to Europe once in a while.

1248
01:13:03,148 --> 01:13:05,031
I know what I'm going 
to do tomorrow ...

1249
01:13:05,031 --> 01:13:08,377
and the next day and next year 
and the hear after that.

1250
01:13:08,377 --> 01:13:13,570
I'm shaking the dust of this crummy little town  
off my feet, and I'm going to see the world ...

1251
01:13:13,570 --> 01:13:16,421
and then I'm going to build things. 
I'm going to build air fields.

1252
01:13:16,421 --> 01:13:19,376
I'm going to build skyscrapers 
a hundred stories high.

1253
01:13:19,376 --> 01:13:22,831
I'm going to build 
a bridge a mile long.

1254
01:13:22,831 --> 01:13:24,595
What is it you want,

1255
01:13:24,595 --> 01:13:26,485
Mary? What? Y-You want the moon?

1256
01:13:26,485 --> 01:13:29,045
If you do, just say the word, 
I'll throw a lasso around it

1257
01:13:29,045 --> 01:13:31,140
and pulls her down for you.

1258
01:13:31,140 --> 01:13:33,610
Buffalo Gals, 
won't you come out tonight,

1259
01:13:33,610 --> 01:13:36,600
Won't you come out tonight, 
Won't you come out tonight.

1260
01:13:36,600 --> 01:13:40,004
Buffalo Gals, 
won't you come out tonight,

1261
01:13:40,004 --> 01:13:42,055
And ...

1262
01:13:48,181 --> 01:13:49,807
- Hi.
- Hi.

1263
01:13:55,355 --> 01:13:56,759
Mary Hatch!

1264
01:13:59,120 --> 01:14:03,319
Wh-Why in the world did you 
ever marry a guy like me?

1265
01:14:03,319 --> 01:14:05,860
To keep from being an old maid.

1266
01:14:05,860 --> 01:14:09,937
You could have married Sam Wainwright 
and anybody else in town.

1267
01:14:09,937 --> 01:14:13,370
I didn't want to marry 
anybody else in town.

1268
01:14:13,370 --> 01:14:15,798
I want my baby to look like you.

1269
01:14:15,798 --> 01:14:17,719
You didn't even have a honeymoon.

1270
01:14:17,719 --> 01:14:21,320
I promised you ... your what?

1271
01:14:21,320 --> 01:14:23,934
My baby.

1272
01:14:23,934 --> 01:14:29,222
You — You-You-You-You-You-You-You ...
Mary, you're on the nest?

1273
01:14:29,222 --> 01:14:31,937
George Bailey lassoes stork.

1274
01:14:31,937 --> 01:14:33,397
Lassoes the stork!

1275
01:14:35,416 --> 01:14:37,214
What do you ...

1276
01:14:37,214 --> 01:14:39,216
You mean ... you-you-you ...

1277
01:14:39,216 --> 01:14:41,438
What-what-what is it, 
a boy or a girl?

1278
01:14:41,438 --> 01:14:42,697
Uh-hm.

1279
01:14:44,757 --> 01:14:49,345
Now, you've probably already guessed 
that George never leaves Bedford Falls.

1280
01:14:49,345 --> 01:14:50,369
No!

1281
01:14:50,369 --> 01:14:53,493
Mary had her baby, a boy.

1282
01:14:53,493 --> 01:14:55,988
Then she had another one, a girl.

1283
01:14:55,988 --> 01:15:01,243
Day after day she worked away remaking 
the old Granville house into a home.

1284
01:15:01,243 --> 01:15:04,962
Night after night, George 
came back late from the office.

1285
01:15:08,548 --> 01:15:10,805
Potter was bearing down hard.

1286
01:15:15,985 --> 01:15:17,731
Then came a war.

1287
01:15:18,389 --> 01:15:22,469
Ma Bailey and Mrs. Hatch joined 
the Red Cross and sewed.

1288
01:15:22,469 --> 01:15:26,719
Mary had two more babies but still 
found time to run the U.S.O.

1289
01:15:26,719 --> 01:15:30,713
Sam Wainwright made a fortune 
in plastic hoods for planes.

1290
01:15:30,713 --> 01:15:33,502
Potter became head of the draft board.

1291
01:15:33,502 --> 01:15:41,641
One-A ... one-A ... one-A

1292
01:15:41,641 --> 01:15:44,462
Gower and Uncle Billy sold war bonds.

1293
01:15:44,462 --> 01:15:49,036
Bert the cop was wounded in 
North Africa, got the Silver Star.

1294
01:15:49,036 --> 01:15:52,895
Ernie, the taxi-driver, 
parachuted into France.

1295
01:15:52,895 --> 01:15:56,328
Marty helped capture the Remagen Bridge.

1296
01:15:56,328 --> 01:16:00,086
Harry, Harry Bailey topped them all.

1297
01:16:00,086 --> 01:16:03,861
A Navy flier, 
he shot down fifteen planes.

1298
01:16:03,861 --> 01:16:08,239
Two of them as they were about to crash 
into a transport full of soldiers.

1299
01:16:09,663 --> 01:16:12,379
- Yes, but George ...
- George?

1300
01:16:12,379 --> 01:16:17,554
Four-F on account of his ear, 
George fought the battle of Bedford Falls.

1301
01:16:17,554 --> 01:16:19,692
Hold on, hold on, hold on now.

1302
01:16:19,692 --> 01:16:21,334
Don't you know there's a war on?

1303
01:16:21,334 --> 01:16:23,533
Air raid warden ...

1304
01:16:32,036 --> 01:16:36,536
paper drives ... scrap drives ...
rubber drives ...

1305
01:16:36,536 --> 01:16:42,112
Like everybody else, 
on V-E day he wept and prayed.

1306
01:16:42,112 --> 01:16:46,875
On V-J day, 
he wept and prayed again.

1307
01:16:46,875 --> 01:16:49,403
Joseph, now show him 
what happened today.

1308
01:16:49,403 --> 01:16:50,728
Yes, sir.

1309
01:16:50,728 --> 01:16:55,625
This morning, day before Christmas, 
about ten A.M., Bedford Falls Time.

1310
01:16:55,625 --> 01:16:58,192
Hi, Ernie, look at that.

1311
01:17:03,444 --> 01:17:04,542
Gonna snow again.

1312
01:17:04,542 --> 01:17:07,841
What do you mean it's gonna snow? 
Look at the headlines.

1313
01:17:07,841 --> 01:17:10,335
I know, I know, George. 
And it's marvelous.

1314
01:17:10,335 --> 01:17:12,133
Commander Harry Bailey!

1315
01:17:12,133 --> 01:17:13,809
Mr. Gower, look at this.

1316
01:17:13,809 --> 01:17:15,873
The second page. 
Now look, this is for you.

1317
01:17:15,873 --> 01:17:17,665
This is for you. That's for you.

1318
01:17:17,665 --> 01:17:19,333
- Thanks.
- See you again.

1319
01:17:20,965 --> 01:17:23,122
Be sure you spell the name right.

1320
01:17:23,122 --> 01:17:25,046
Hello, Billy, how are you?

1321
01:17:33,202 --> 01:17:35,934
Extra! Extra! Read all about it!

1322
01:17:35,934 --> 01:17:38,264
George! George! It's Harry now 
on long distance from Washington.

1323
01:17:38,264 --> 01:17:41,249
- Harry! What do you know about that!
- He reversed the charges. It's okay, isn't it?

1324
01:17:41,249 --> 01:17:43,899
Reverse the charges ...
of course it's for a hero.

1325
01:17:43,899 --> 01:17:45,402
Harry ...

1326
01:17:45,402 --> 01:17:48,377
Oh, you old seven times 
of a son of a gun.

1327
01:17:48,377 --> 01:17:49,664
Congratulations!

1328
01:17:49,664 --> 01:17:51,378
How's mother standing it?

1329
01:17:51,378 --> 01:17:52,810
She did?

1330
01:17:52,810 --> 01:17:53,910
What do you know ...

1331
01:17:53,910 --> 01:17:55,491
Mother had lunch 
with the President's wife.

1332
01:17:55,491 --> 01:17:56,770
Wait till Martha hears about this.

1333
01:17:56,770 --> 01:17:58,629
- What did they have to eat?
- Wha-What did they have to eat?

1334
01:17:58,629 --> 01:18:03,427
H-H-Harry, you should see what they're 
cooking up in the town for you.

1335
01:18:03,427 --> 01:18:04,458
Oh, they are?

1336
01:18:04,458 --> 01:18:06,409
The Navy's going to fly mother 
home this afternoon.

1337
01:18:06,409 --> 01:18:08,171
In a plane?

1338
01:18:08,171 --> 01:18:10,174
What? Uncle Billy?

1339
01:18:10,174 --> 01:18:12,240
- Has Uncle Billy come in yet?
- No, he stopped at the bank first.

1340
01:18:12,240 --> 01:18:14,276
No, he's not here right now, Harry. 
But look ...

1341
01:18:14,276 --> 01:18:15,844
- George ...
- ... tell me about it.

1342
01:18:15,844 --> 01:18:17,937
... George, tha-that man's here again.

1343
01:18:17,937 --> 01:18:19,623
- What man?
- B-B-Bank ... examiner.

1344
01:18:19,623 --> 01:18:21,087
Oh, oh. Uh, uh,

1345
01:18:21,087 --> 01:18:23,295
Harry, talk to Eustace for a minute, 
will you?

1346
01:18:23,295 --> 01:18:25,355
I'll be right back. Well ...

1347
01:18:25,355 --> 01:18:27,357
- Harry ...
- Good morning, sir.

1348
01:18:27,357 --> 01:18:28,677
Carter, bank examiner.

1349
01:18:28,677 --> 01:18:31,089
- Mr. Carter, Merry Christmas.
- Merry Christmas.

1350
01:18:31,089 --> 01:18:32,932
We're all excited around here.

1351
01:18:32,932 --> 01:18:34,902
My brother just got 
the Congressional Medal of Honor.

1352
01:18:34,902 --> 01:18:36,035
The president just decorated him.

1353
01:18:36,035 --> 01:18:37,867
Well, I guess they do those things.

1354
01:18:37,867 --> 01:18:39,649
Well, I trust you had a good year.

1355
01:18:39,649 --> 01:18:40,935
Good year?

1356
01:18:40,935 --> 01:18:44,301
Uh, well, between you and me, 
Mr. Carter, we're broke.

1357
01:18:44,301 --> 01:18:47,820
Yeah, very funny.

1358
01:18:47,820 --> 01:18:50,666
Uh, w-well ... 
Now, come right in here, Mr. Carter.

1359
01:18:50,666 --> 01:18:55,212
Oh, I shouldn't wonder when you okay 
reverse charges on personal long distance calls.

1360
01:18:55,212 --> 01:18:56,243
George, shall we hang up?

1361
01:18:56,243 --> 01:18:58,441
No, no. He wants to talk to 
Uncle Billy. You just hold on.

1362
01:18:58,441 --> 01:19:01,312
Now, if you'll cooperate, I'd 
like to finish with you by tonight.

1363
01:19:01,312 --> 01:19:04,149
I want to spend Christmas 
in Elmira with my family.

1364
01:19:04,149 --> 01:19:05,572
I don't blame you at all, Mr. Carter.

1365
01:19:05,572 --> 01:19:07,807
Just step right in here. 
We'll fix you up.

1366
01:19:07,807 --> 01:19:11,585
December twenty-fourth ...

1367
01:19:16,794 --> 01:19:19,698
Eight thousand.

1368
