01:32:42,977 --> 01:32:44,947
Please help me, Mr. Potter.

1604
01:32:44,947 --> 01:32:46,641
Help me, won't you, please?

1605
01:32:46,641 --> 01:32:48,542
Can't you see 
what it means to my family?

1606
01:32:48,542 --> 01:32:51,479
I'll pay any sort of a bonus 
on the loan, any interest ...

1607
01:32:51,479 --> 01:32:53,219
if you still want the 
Building and Loan. I'm ...

1608
01:32:53,219 --> 01:32:56,866
George, could it possibly be there's 
a slight discrepancy in the books?

1609
01:32:56,866 --> 01:32:58,253
No, sir. There's nothing 
wrong with the books.

1610
01:32:58,253 --> 01:32:59,777
I've just misplaced 
eight thousand dollars.

1611
01:32:59,777 --> 01:33:01,490
I can't find it anywhere.

1612
01:33:01,490 --> 01:33:04,720
You misplaced eight thousand dollars?

1613
01:33:04,720 --> 01:33:05,826
Yes, sir.

1614
01:33:08,649 --> 01:33:10,393
Have you notified the police?

1615
01:33:10,393 --> 01:33:12,205
No, sir. 
I — I didn't want the publicity.

1616
01:33:12,205 --> 01:33:14,031
Harry's homecoming tomorrow ...

1617
01:33:14,031 --> 01:33:16,408
They're gonna believe that one.

1618
01:33:16,408 --> 01:33:18,785
What've you been doing, George?

1619
01:33:18,785 --> 01:33:20,482
Playing the market 
with the company's money?

1620
01:33:20,482 --> 01:33:21,716
No, sir, no, sir. I haven't.

1621
01:33:21,716 --> 01:33:23,738
What is it, a woman then?

1622
01:33:23,738 --> 01:33:27,836
You know, it's all over town that 
you've been giving money to Violet Bick.

1623
01:33:27,836 --> 01:33:30,177
- What!
- Not that it makes any difference to me,

1624
01:33:30,177 --> 01:33:31,437
but why did you come to me?

1625
01:33:31,437 --> 01:33:34,205
Why don't you go to Sam Wainwright 
and ask him for the money?

1626
01:33:34,205 --> 01:33:35,785
I can't get ahold of him. 
He's in Europe.

1627
01:33:35,785 --> 01:33:37,395
Well, what about all your other friends?

1628
01:33:37,395 --> 01:33:39,194
They don't have that kind of money, 
Mr. Potter.

1629
01:33:39,194 --> 01:33:41,647
You know that. You're the only one 
in town that can help me.

1630
01:33:41,647 --> 01:33:43,526
I see.

1631
01:33:43,526 --> 01:33:47,114
I've suddenly become quite important.

1632
01:33:47,114 --> 01:33:50,023
Wha-What kind of security 
would I have, George?

1633
01:33:50,023 --> 01:33:53,315
- Have you got any stocks?
- No, sir.

1634
01:33:53,315 --> 01:33:56,184
Bonds? Real estate? 
Collateral of any kind?

1635
01:33:56,706 --> 01:34:01,007
I have some life insurance, 
a fifteen thousand dollar policy.

1636
01:34:01,007 --> 01:34:03,282
Yes ... how much is your equity in it?

1637
01:34:03,282 --> 01:34:07,090
- Five hundred dollars.
- Five hundred dollars!

1638
01:34:07,090 --> 01:34:11,370
And you ask me 
to lend you eight thousand.

1639
01:34:11,370 --> 01:34:12,518
Look at you.

1640
01:34:12,518 --> 01:34:14,745
You used to be so cocky!

1641
01:34:14,745 --> 01:34:18,346
You were going to go out 
and conquer the world.

1642
01:34:18,346 --> 01:34:23,895
You once called me a warped, 
frustrated old man.

1643
01:34:23,895 --> 01:34:27,805
What are you 
but a warped frustrated young man?

1644
01:34:27,805 --> 01:34:33,214
A miserable little clerk crawling in here 
on your hands and knees and begging for help.

1645
01:34:33,214 --> 01:34:35,313
No securities, no stocks, no bonds,

1646
01:34:35,313 --> 01:34:42,014
nothing but a miserable little five hundred 
dollar equity in a life insurance policy.

1647
01:34:42,014 --> 01:34:44,902
You're worth more dead than alive.

1648
01:34:44,902 --> 01:34:48,081
Why don't you go to the riff-raff 
you love so much ...

1649
01:34:48,081 --> 01:34:51,010
ask them to let you 
have eight thousand?

1650
01:34:51,010 --> 01:34:52,228
You know why?

1651
01:34:52,228 --> 01:34:54,964
Because they'd run you 
out of town on a rail.

1652
01:34:54,964 --> 01:34:58,297
But I tell you what I'm going 
to do for you, George.

1653
01:34:58,297 --> 01:35:01,595
Since the state examiner is still here,

1654
01:35:01,595 --> 01:35:04,194
as a stock holder 
of the Building and Loan,

1655
01:35:04,194 --> 01:35:07,594
I'm going to swear out a warrant 
for your arrest.

1656
01:35:07,594 --> 01:35:12,254
Misappropriation of funds, 
manipulation, malfeasance ...

1657
01:35:13,134 --> 01:35:15,648
All right, George, go ahead, George.

1658
01:35:15,648 --> 01:35:18,776
You can't hide in a 
little town like this.

1659
01:35:18,776 --> 01:35:21,221
Bill? This is Potter.

1660
01:35:34,038 --> 01:35:36,975
Joe! Merry Christmas!

1661
01:35:36,975 --> 01:35:38,622
- Glad you come.
- Thank you.

1662
01:35:38,622 --> 01:35:41,408
- How about some of that good spaghetti?
- We got everything.

1663
01:35:53,190 --> 01:35:54,824
God ...

1664
01:35:57,851 --> 01:35:59,101
Oh, God ...

1665
01:36:03,936 --> 01:36:05,835
Dear Father in Heaven,

1666
01:36:09,015 --> 01:36:13,116
I'm not a praying man, but 
if you're up there,

1667
01:36:13,116 --> 01:36:18,816
and you can hear me, 
show me the way.

1668
01:36:18,816 --> 01:36:22,961
I'm at the end of my rope. 
I ...

1669
01:36:22,961 --> 01:36:25,678
Show me the way, God.

1670
01:36:30,164 --> 01:36:31,537
Are you all right, George?

1671
01:36:31,537 --> 01:36:33,412
Want someone to take you home?

1672
01:36:36,227 --> 01:36:38,628
Why you drink so much, my friend?

1673
01:36:38,628 --> 01:36:42,497
Please go home, Mr. Bailey. 
This is Christmas Eve.

1674
01:36:42,497 --> 01:36:45,725
Bailey? Which Bailey?

1675
01:36:45,725 --> 01:36:47,950
This is Mr. George Bailey.

1676
01:36:52,021 --> 01:36:54,852
And the next time you talk to my 
wife like that, you'll get worse.

1677
01:36:54,852 --> 01:36:56,355
She cried for an hour.

1678
01:36:56,355 --> 01:36:58,825
It isn't enough she slaves 
teaching your stupid kids

1679
01:36:58,825 --> 01:37:00,771
how to read and write, and you 
have to bawl her out, eh.

1680
01:37:00,771 --> 01:37:02,011
You get out of here, Mr. Welch!

1681
01:37:02,011 --> 01:37:03,530
Now wait. 
I want to pay for my drink.

1682
01:37:03,530 --> 01:37:05,482
Never mind the money. 
You get out of here quick.

1683
01:37:05,482 --> 01:37:08,600
- All right.
- You hit my best friend. Get out!

1684
01:37:13,874 --> 01:37:15,633
You all right, George?

1685
01:37:15,633 --> 01:37:16,802
Who was that?

1686
01:37:16,802 --> 01:37:19,003
He gone. No worry.

1687
01:37:19,003 --> 01:37:21,630
His name is Welch. 
He no come in to my place no more.

1688
01:37:21,630 --> 01:37:24,926
Oh, Welch. 
That's what I get for praying.

1689
01:37:24,926 --> 01:37:26,958
The last time he come in here. 
You hear that, Nick?

1690
01:37:26,958 --> 01:37:28,166
Yes, you bet.

1691
01:37:28,166 --> 01:37:31,838
Where's my insurance policy? 
Oh, here.

1692
01:37:31,838 --> 01:37:33,693
- Oh, no, please, no go out this way, Mr. Bailey.
- I'm all right.

1693
01:37:33,693 --> 01:37:35,835
No, no, you no feel so good. 
Sit down and rest.

1694
01:37:35,835 --> 01:37:38,767
- I'm all right.
- Please no go away. Please!

1695
01:37:57,344 --> 01:37:58,650
What do you think you're doing?

1696
01:38:01,745 --> 01:38:03,203
Now look what you did.

1697
01:38:03,203 --> 01:38:05,518
My great-grandfather planted this tree.

1698
01:38:06,447 --> 01:38:08,518
Hey, you! Hey, you!

1699
01:38:09,193 --> 01:38:10,984
Come back here, you drunken fool!

1700
01:38:10,984 --> 01:38:12,815
Get this car out of here!

1701
01:38:20,912 --> 01:38:23,121
Hey, what's the matter with you? 
Look where you're going!

1702
01:39:11,343 --> 01:39:12,801
Help!

1703
01:39:14,056 --> 01:39:18,624
Help! Help! Help!

1704
01:39:20,357 --> 01:39:22,949
Help! Help!

1705
01:39:24,678 --> 01:39:26,930
Help!

1706
01:39:29,189 --> 01:39:33,559
Help! Help! Help! Help!

1707
01:39:35,733 --> 01:39:37,097
Help!

1708
01:39:38,215 --> 01:39:42,330
Help! Help! Help!

1709
01:39:58,683 --> 01:40:00,975
I didn't have time to get 
some stylish underwear.

1710
01:40:00,975 --> 01:40:03,435
My wife gave me this 
on my last birthday.

1711
01:40:04,483 --> 01:40:06,325
I passed away in it.

1712
01:40:09,794 --> 01:40:12,503
Oh, Tom Sawyer's drying out, too.

1713
01:40:15,905 --> 01:40:18,700
You should read the new book 
Mark Twain's writing now.

1714
01:40:19,930 --> 01:40:21,895
How did you happen to fall in?

1715
01:40:21,895 --> 01:40:25,431
I didn't fall in. 
I jumped in to save George.

1716
01:40:25,431 --> 01:40:28,520
You what? 
To ... to save me?

1717
01:40:28,520 --> 01:40:31,707
Well, I did, didn't I? You didn't 
go through with it, did you?

1718
01:40:31,707 --> 01:40:33,924
- Go through with what?
- Suicide.

1719
01:40:33,924 --> 01:40:37,109
Well, it's against the law 
to commit suicide around here.

1720
01:40:37,109 --> 01:40:39,979
Yeah, it's against the law 
where I come from, too.

1721
01:40:39,979 --> 01:40:42,767
- Where do you come from?
- Heaven.

1722
01:40:47,532 --> 01:40:50,558
I had to act quickly. 
That's why I jumped in.

1723
01:40:50,558 --> 01:40:53,075
I knew if I were drowning 
you'd try to save me.

1724
01:40:53,075 --> 01:40:56,227
And you see, you did, 
and that's how I saved you.

1725
01:40:56,227 --> 01:40:58,399
Very funny.

1726
01:40:58,399 --> 01:41:00,469
Your lip's bleeding, George.

1727
01:41:00,469 --> 01:41:04,758
Yeah, I got a bust in the jaw in 
answer to a prayer a little bit ago.

1728
01:41:04,758 --> 01:41:08,636
Oh, no, no, no, George, 
I'm the answer to your prayer.

1729
01:41:08,636 --> 01:41:10,670
That's why I was sent down here.

1730
01:41:11,532 --> 01:41:13,012
How do you know my name?

1731
01:41:13,012 --> 01:41:16,599
Oh, I know all about you. I've 
watched you grow up from a little boy.

1732
01:41:16,599 --> 01:41:19,472
- What are you, a mind reader or something?
- Oh, no.

1733
01:41:19,472 --> 01:41:24,076
- Well, who are you then?
- Clarence Odbody, A-S-2.

1734
01:41:24,076 --> 01:41:28,786
Odbody ... A-S-2. 
Wh-Wh-What's that A-S-2?

1735
01:41:28,786 --> 01:41:30,328
Angel Second Class.

1736
01:41:40,984 --> 01:41:42,681
Cheerio, my good man.

1737
01:41:46,868 --> 01:41:48,341
Oh, brother ...

1738
01:41:53,082 --> 01:41:55,267
I wonder what Martini 
put in those drinks?

1739
01:41:57,800 --> 01:42:00,179
Hey, what's ... with you ...

1740
01:42:00,179 --> 01:42:02,625
wh-wh-what-did you say 
just a minute ago?

1741
01:42:02,625 --> 01:42:04,304
Why'd you want to save me?

1742
01:42:04,304 --> 01:42:08,438
That's what I was sent down for. 
I'm your guardian angel.

1743
01:42:08,438 --> 01:42:10,577
I wouldn't be a bit surprised.

1744
01:42:10,577 --> 01:42:13,690
Ridiculous of you to think of 
killing yourself for money.

1745
01:42:13,690 --> 01:42:16,439
- Eight thousand dollars.
- Yeah, I'll say. Just things like that.

1746
01:42:16,439 --> 01:42:18,153
Now how do you know that?

1747
01:42:18,153 --> 01:42:19,983
I told you. I'm your guardian angel.

1748
01:42:19,983 --> 01:42:21,814
I know everything about you.

1749
01:42:23,153 --> 01:42:26,382
Well, you look about like 
the kind of an angel I'd get.

1750
01:42:26,382 --> 01:42:28,231
Sort of a fallen angel, aren't you?

1751
01:42:28,231 --> 01:42:29,399
What happened to your wings?

1752
01:42:29,399 --> 01:42:33,045
I haven't won my wings yet. 
That's why I'm an angel second class.

1753
01:42:37,813 --> 01:42:41,245
I don't know whether I like it very much being 
seen around with an angel without any wings.

1754
01:42:41,245 --> 01:42:45,027
Oh, I — I've got to earn them 
and you'll help me, won't you?

1755
01:42:45,027 --> 01:42:49,855
- Sure, sure. How?
- By letting me help you.

1756
01:42:51,534 --> 01:42:52,605
Only one way you can help me.

1757
01:42:52,605 --> 01:42:54,659
Y-You don't happen to have 
eight thousand bucks on you?

1758
01:42:54,659 --> 01:42:57,267
Oh, no, no. 
We don't use money in heaven.

1759
01:42:57,267 --> 01:43:00,550
Oh, that's right, I keep forgetting.

1760
01:43:00,550 --> 01:43:02,485
Comes in pretty handy down here, bub.

1761
01:43:02,485 --> 01:43:05,256
Oh, tut, tut, tut.

1762
01:43:05,256 --> 01:43:07,855
I found it out a little late.

1763
01:43:07,855 --> 01:43:09,979
I'm worth more dead than alive.

1764
01:43:09,979 --> 01:43:14,215
Now look, you mustn't talk like that. 
I won't get my wings with that attitude.

1765
01:43:14,215 --> 01:43:16,745
You just don't know 
all that you've done.

1766
01:43:16,745 --> 01:43:17,948
If it hadn't been for you ...

1767
01:43:17,948 --> 01:43:20,847
Yeah, if it hadn't been for me, 
everybody'd be a lot better off.

1768
01:43:20,847 --> 01:43:22,915
My wife, and my kids, and my friends.

1769
01:43:22,915 --> 01:43:26,228
And my ... Look, little fellow, why, you 
go off and haunt somebody else, will you?

1770
01:43:26,228 --> 01:43:29,014
No, no, you don't understand. 
I've got my job.

1771
01:43:29,014 --> 01:43:30,828
Aw, shut up, will you?

1772
01:43:35,015 --> 01:43:38,092
Hmmm, this isn't gonna be so easy.

1773
01:43:42,467 --> 01:43:47,364
Yeah! So you still think killing yourself 
would make everyone feel happier, eh?

1774
01:43:48,807 --> 01:43:51,233
Oh, I don't know. 
I guess you're right.

1775
01:43:52,930 --> 01:43:55,956
I suppose it would have been better 
if I'd never been born at all.

1776
01:43:55,956 --> 01:43:59,399
- What'd you say?
- I said I wish I'd never been born.

1777
01:43:59,399 --> 01:44:02,308
Oh, you mustn't say things like that.

1778
01:44:02,308 --> 01:44:03,629
You ...

1779
01:44:03,629 --> 01:44:05,802
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

1780
01:44:05,802 --> 01:44:07,964
That's an idea.

1781
01:44:07,964 --> 01:44:12,714
What do you think? 
Yeah, that'll do it.

1782
01:44:12,714 --> 01:44:13,834
All right.

1783
01:44:16,829 --> 01:44:18,593
You've got your wish.

1784
01:44:18,593 --> 01:44:20,314
You've never been born.

1785
01:44:25,412 --> 01:44:27,786
You don't have to make 
all that fuss about it.

1786
01:44:29,568 --> 01:44:30,986
What did you say?

1787
01:44:30,986 --> 01:44:33,552
You've never been born. 
You don't exist.

1788
01:44:33,552 --> 01:44:34,857
You haven't a care in the world.

1789
01:44:34,857 --> 01:44:38,378
No worries, no obligations, 
no eight thousand dollars to get,

1790
01:44:38,378 --> 01:44:40,211
no Potter looking for you 
with the sheriff.

1791
01:44:40,211 --> 01:44:43,057
- Say something else in that ear.
- Sure. You can hear out of it.

1792
01:44:43,800 --> 01:44:46,129
Well, that's the doggonedest thing.

1793
01:44:46,129 --> 01:44:48,600
I haven't heard anything out 
of that ear since I was a kid.

1794
01:44:48,600 --> 01:44:50,857
Must have been that jump in 
that cold water.

1795
01:44:50,857 --> 01:44:53,095
Your lip's stopped 
bleeding, too, George.

1796
01:44:58,432 --> 01:44:59,957
What do you know about that?

1797
01:45:01,110 --> 01:45:02,174
What's happened?

1798
01:45:03,462 --> 01:45:05,853
It's stopped snowing out, hasn't it?

1799
01:45:05,853 --> 01:45:08,468
Well, I, uh ...
What's happened here?

1800
01:45:08,468 --> 01:45:10,266
What I need is a couple of 
good stiff drinks.

1801
01:45:10,266 --> 01:45:12,320
How about you, angel, 
you want a drink?

1802
01:45:14,358 --> 01:45:16,394
Come on, soon as 
these clothes of ours are dry ...

1803
01:45:16,394 --> 01:45:18,628
Those are dry.

1804
01:45:18,628 --> 01:45:20,257
What do you know about that?

1805
01:45:20,257 --> 01:45:21,563
Stove's hotter than I thought.

1806
01:45:21,563 --> 01:45:24,981
Now, come on, get your clothes on, 
and we'll stroll up to my car and get ...

1807
01:45:24,981 --> 01:45:28,090
Oh, I'm sorry. 
I'll stroll, you fly.

1808
01:45:28,090 --> 01:45:29,870
I can't fly. 
I haven't got my wings.

1809
01:45:29,870 --> 01:45:31,702
You haven't got your wings. 
Yeah, that's right.

1810
01:45:38,309 --> 01:45:39,581
What's the matter?

1811
01:45:39,581 --> 01:45:42,452
Well, this is where I left 
my car and it isn't here.

1812
01:45:42,452 --> 01:45:43,706
You have no car.

1813
01:45:43,706 --> 01:45:47,481
Well, I had a car and it was right 
here. I guess somebody moved it.

1814
01:45:47,481 --> 01:45:50,193
- Good evening.
- Oh, say ... Hey ...

1815
01:45:50,193 --> 01:45:51,883
wh-where's my car.

1816
01:45:51,883 --> 01:45:53,859
- I beg your pardon?
- My car, my car.

1817
01:45:53,859 --> 01:45:56,340
I'm the fellow that owns the car 
that ran into your tree.

1818
01:45:56,340 --> 01:45:58,385
What tree?
What do you mean, what tree?

1819
01:45:58,385 --> 01:46:00,643
This tree. Here. I ran into it.

1820
01:46:00,643 --> 01:46:04,484
Cut a big gash 
in the side of it there.

1821
01:46:08,178 --> 01:46:10,539
You must mean two other trees.

1822
01:46:10,539 --> 01:46:11,776
You had me worried.

1823
01:46:11,776 --> 01:46:14,018
One of the oldest 
trees in Pottersville.

1824
01:46:14,018 --> 01:46:16,891
Pottersville. 
Why, you mean Bedford Falls.

1825
01:46:16,891 --> 01:46:18,759
I mean Pottersville.

1826
01:46:18,759 --> 01:46:20,711
Don't you think 
I know where I live?

1827
01:46:20,711 --> 01:46:22,003
What's the matter with you?

1828
01:46:28,641 --> 01:46:31,955
Oh, I don't know. 
Either I'm off my nut, or he is.

1829
01:46:31,955 --> 01:46:33,163
... or you are.

1830
01:46:33,939 --> 01:46:35,402
It isn't me!

1831
01:46:35,402 --> 01:46:39,019
Well, maybe I left the car up at Martini's. 
Well, come on, Gabriel.

1832
01:46:39,019 --> 01:46:41,256
- Clarence!
- Clarence! Clarence!

1833
01:46:47,320 --> 01:46:48,356
That's all right. Go on in.

1834
01:46:48,356 --> 01:46:51,486
Martini is a friend of mine.

1835
01:46:51,486 --> 01:46:53,420
There's a place to sit down, sit down.

1836
01:47:00,472 --> 01:47:03,101
Oh, hello, Nick. 
Hey, where's Martini?

1837
01:47:03,101 --> 01:47:04,993
- You want a Martini?
- No, no, Martini.

1838
01:47:04,993 --> 01:47:07,329
- Your boss. Where is he?
- Look, I'm the boss.

1839
01:47:07,329 --> 01:47:08,633
You want a drink or don't you?

1840
01:47:08,633 --> 01:47:10,996
Okay, all right. Double bourbon, 
will you? Quick, huh.

1841
01:47:10,996 --> 01:47:12,182
Okay.

1842
01:47:15,398 --> 01:47:16,975
What's yours?

1843
01:47:16,975 --> 01:47:18,569
I was just thinking.

1844
01:47:18,569 --> 01:47:22,278
Uh ... It's been so long 
since I ...

1845
01:47:22,278 --> 01:47:25,815
Look, Mister, I'm standing here waiting 
for you to make up your mind.

1846
01:47:25,815 --> 01:47:27,461
That's a good man.

1847
01:47:27,461 --> 01:47:34,171
I was just thinking, uh, 
of a flaming rum punch.

1848
01:47:34,171 --> 01:47:36,665
No, it's not cold enough for that. 
Not nearly cold enough.

1849
01:47:36,665 --> 01:47:37,932
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

1850
01:47:37,932 --> 01:47:39,851
I got it.

1851
01:47:39,851 --> 01:47:43,471
Mulled wine, heavy on the cinnamon 
and light on the cloves.

1852
01:47:43,471 --> 01:47:45,423
Off with you, me lad, and be lively!

1853
01:47:45,423 --> 01:47:50,392
Hey, look, Mister, we serve hard drinks 
in here for men who want to get drunk fast.

1854
01:47:50,392 --> 01:47:55,221
And we don't need any characters around 
to give the joint atmosphere. Is that clear?

1855
01:47:55,221 --> 01:47:57,906
Or do I have to slip you 
my left for a convincer?

1856
01:47:57,906 --> 01:47:59,050
What's he talking about?

1857
01:47:59,050 --> 01:48:04,546
Nick, Nick, just give him 
the same as mine. He's okay.

1858
01:48:04,546 --> 01:48:05,744
Okay.

1859
01:48:07,152 --> 01:48:08,596
What's the matter with him?

1860
01:48:08,596 --> 01:48:10,750
I never saw Nick act like that before.

1861
01:48:10,750 --> 01:48:14,169
You'll see a lot of strange 
things from now on.

1862
01:48:14,169 --> 01:48:15,612
Oh, yeah.

1863
01:48:16,918 --> 01:48:22,349
Hey, li-li-little fellow, 
you worry me.

1864
01:48:22,349 --> 01:48:25,845
- You know, y-y-you got someplace to sleep?
- No.

1865
01:48:25,845 --> 01:48:27,491
You don't, huh?

1866
01:48:27,491 --> 01:48:31,079
- Well, y-y-you got any money?
- No.

1867
01:48:31,079 --> 01:48:32,666
No wonder you jumped in the river.

1868
01:48:32,666 --> 01:48:36,269
I jumped in the river to save you 
so I could get my wings.

1869
01:48:36,269 --> 01:48:38,311
- Oh, that's right.
- Oh-oh.

1870
01:48:40,316 --> 01:48:42,408
- Somebody's just made it.
- Made what?

1871
01:48:42,408 --> 01:48:46,917
Every time you hear a bell ring, it means 
that some angel's just got his wings.

1872
01:48:52,247 --> 01:48:59,584
Look, I think maybe you better not 
mention getting your wings around here.

1873
01:48:59,584 --> 01:49:02,150
Why? 
Don't they believe in angels?

1874
01:49:02,150 --> 01:49:05,744
A ... Yeah, 
they believe in angels.

1875
01:49:05,744 --> 01:49:08,615
Oh, oh! Why should they be 
surprised when they see one?

1876
01:49:11,372 --> 01:49:15,098
Aw, he never grew up. He's ...

1877
01:49:15,098 --> 01:49:17,051
How old are you, anyway, Clarence?

1878
01:49:17,051 --> 01:49:22,311
Two hundred and ninety-three, 
uh, next May.

1879
01:49:22,970 --> 01:49:24,426
That does it!

1880
01:49:24,426 --> 01:49:27,860
Out you two pixies go, 
through the door or out the window.

1881
01:49:27,860 --> 01:49:29,080
Look, Nick, what's wrong?

1882
01:49:29,080 --> 01:49:32,055
And that's another thing. 
Where do you come off calling me Nick?

1883
01:49:32,055 --> 01:49:33,599
Well, Nick, that's your name.

1884
01:49:33,599 --> 01:49:37,888
What's that got to do with it? 
I don't know you from Adam's off ox.

1885
01:49:37,888 --> 01:49:40,488
Hey! Hey, you, rummy there! 
Come here! Come here!

1886
01:49:44,286 --> 01:49:47,403
Didn't I tell you never to come 
panhandling around here, huh?

1887
01:49:54,956 --> 01:49:56,352
Mr. Gower!

1888
01:49:57,539 --> 01:49:58,773
Mr. Gower!

1889
01:50:00,506 --> 01:50:02,612
What ... what is he ...

1890
01:50:02,612 --> 01:50:05,042
Mr. Gower! This is George Bailey!

1891
01:50:06,365 --> 01:50:11,407
- Don't you know me?
- No. No.

1892
01:50:11,407 --> 01:50:12,898
Throw 'em out. Throw 'em out!

1893
01:50:12,898 --> 01:50:16,097
Mr. Gower ... Hey, what is ...

1894
01:50:16,097 --> 01:50:18,475
Hey, Nick, Nick ... 
Isn't that Mr. Gower, the druggist?

1895
01:50:18,475 --> 01:50:20,614
You know, that's another reason 
for me not to like you.

1896
01:50:20,614 --> 01:50:24,152
That rum head spent twenty years 
in jail for poisoning a kid.

1897
01:50:24,152 --> 01:50:26,598
If you know him, you must be 
a jailbird yourself.

1898
01:50:26,598 --> 01:50:29,299
Uh, would you show these 
gentlemen to the door?

1899
01:50:29,299 --> 01:50:31,253
Sure. This way, gentlemen.

1900
01:50:37,010 --> 01:50:38,906
Stay out! Stay out!

1901
01:50:38,906 --> 01:50:40,141
Hey! Get me!

1902
01:50:40,611 --> 01:50:42,103
I'm giving out wings!

1903
01:50:44,602 --> 01:50:46,228
You see, George, you were not there

1904
01:50:46,228 --> 01:50:48,761
to stop Gower from putting 
that poison into the capsule ...

1905
01:50:48,761 --> 01:50:50,016
What do you mean I wasn't there?

1906
01:50:50,016 --> 01:50:54,730
I remember distinctly. What the ...

1907
01:50:54,730 --> 01:50:57,552
hey, what's going on around here?

1908
01:50:57,552 --> 01:51:02,252
Why, this ought to be Martini's place.

1909
01:51:08,636 --> 01:51:10,428
Look, who are you?

1910
01:51:10,428 --> 01:51:13,067
I told you, George. 
I'm your guardian angel.

1911
01:51:13,067 --> 01:51:14,755
Yeah, yeah, I know. 
You told me that.

1912
01:51:20,938 --> 01:51:23,155
What else are you? What are you?

1913
01:51:23,155 --> 01:51:25,261
- You are hypnotist?
- No, of course not.

1914
01:51:25,261 --> 01:51:28,131
Well, then why am I seeing 
all these strange things?

1915
01:51:28,131 --> 01:51:30,322
Don't you understand, George?

1916
01:51:30,322 --> 01:51:32,598
It's because you were not born.

1917
01:51:32,598 --> 01:51:34,330
Then if I wasn't born, who am I?

1918
01:51:34,330 --> 01:51:37,158
You're nobody. You have no identity.

1919
01:51:37,158 --> 01:51:39,585
Oh, what do you mean, no identity? 
My name's George Bailey.

1920
01:51:39,585 --> 01:51:41,641
There is no George Bailey.

1921
01:51:42,946 --> 01:51:51,457
You have no papers, no cards, no driver's 
license, no 4-F card, no insurance policy.

1922
01:51:51,457 --> 01:51:53,259
They're not there, either.

1923
01:51:54,669 --> 01:51:57,545
- What?
- Zuzu's petals.

1924
01:52:02,550 --> 01:52:05,388
You've been given a great gift, George ...

1925
01:52:05,388 --> 01:52:08,790
a chance to see what the world 
would be like without you.

1926
01:52:11,303 --> 01:52:14,207
Now wait a minute here. 
Wait a minute here.

1927
01:52:15,888 --> 01:52:19,289
Aw, this is some sort of a 
funny dream I'm having here.

1928
01:52:19,289 --> 01:52:21,206
So long, Mister, I — I'm going home.

1929
01:52:21,206 --> 01:52:23,760
- Home? What home?
- Now shut up! Cut it out!

1930
01:52:24,606 --> 01:52:27,318
You're — You're — You're crazy. 
That's what I think.

1931
01:52:27,318 --> 01:52:30,422
You're — You're screwy 
and you're driving me crazy, too!

1932
01:52:30,422 --> 01:52:31,830
I'm seeing things here.

1933
01:52:31,830 --> 01:52:33,869
I'm going home 
and see my wife and family.

1934
01:52:33,869 --> 01:52:36,242
You understand that? 
And I'm going home alone!

1935
01:52:39,494 --> 01:52:42,978
How am I doing, Joseph? Thanks.

1936
01:52:43,613 --> 01:52:45,327
No, I didn't have a drink!

1937
01:53:36,109 --> 01:53:37,940
Hey, hey.

1938
01:53:37,940 --> 01:53:40,482
- Where did the Building and Loan move to?
- The building and what?

1939
01:53:40,482 --> 01:53:42,178
The Bailey Building and Loan. 
It was up there.

1940
01:53:42,178 --> 01:53:44,379
They went out of business years ago.

1941
01:53:44,379 --> 01:53:46,159
That guy is a liar!

1942
01:53:46,159 --> 01:53:48,165
I know everything's shot in this town.

1943
01:53:48,165 --> 01:53:52,285
- I know ...
- Hey, Violet.

1944
01:53:53,523 --> 01:53:56,327
Hey, listen, that's Violet Bick!

1945
01:53:56,327 --> 01:53:58,441
- I know. I know.
- I know that girl.

1946
01:53:58,441 --> 01:54:00,016
Take a walk. Beat it.

1947
01:54:02,346 --> 01:54:04,195
Hey, Ernie, Ernie ...

1948
01:54:06,184 --> 01:54:08,332
Ernie, take me home. 
I've gone off my nut!

1949
01:54:08,332 --> 01:54:09,885
- Where do you live?
- Aw, now, doggone it,

1950
01:54:09,885 --> 01:54:11,325
Ernie, don't you start 
pulling that stuff.

1951
01:54:11,325 --> 01:54:13,250
You know where I live. 
Three-twenty Sycamore.

1952
01:54:13,250 --> 01:54:15,798
- Now hurry up.
- Okay. Three-twenty Sycamore?

1953
01:54:15,798 --> 01:54:18,945
- Yeah, yeah, hurry up. Zuzu's sick.
- All right. All right.

1954
01:54:20,009 --> 01:54:22,081
Look here, Ernie, 
straighten me out here.

1955
01:54:22,081 --> 01:54:23,815
Look, I — I've got some bad liquor 
or something.

1956
01:54:23,815 --> 01:54:26,274
I want you to listen to me. 
Now, you are Ernie Bishop,

1957
01:54:26,274 --> 01:54:29,213
and you live in Bailey Park with your 
wife and kid? That's right, isn't it?

1958
01:54:29,213 --> 01:54:30,296
You seen my wife?

1959
01:54:30,296 --> 01:54:33,787
Seen your wife! I've been to 
your house a hundred times.

1960
01:54:33,787 --> 01:54:35,075
Look, bud, what's the idea?

1961
01:54:35,075 --> 01:54:38,743
I live in a shack in Potter's Field and my wife 
ran away three years ago and took the kid ...

1962
01:54:38,743 --> 01:54:41,360
And I ain't never seen you 
before in my life, see?

1963
01:54:41,360 --> 01:54:43,812
Okay. Just step on it. 
Just get me home.

1964
01:55:01,929 --> 01:55:03,963
- Is this the place?
- Of course, it's the place.

1965
01:55:03,963 --> 01:55:06,729
Well, this house ain't been 
lived in for twenty years.

1966
01:55:13,337 --> 01:55:14,440
What's up, Ernie?

1967
01:55:14,440 --> 01:55:16,833
I don't know, but we'd better keep 
our eye on this guy.

1968
01:55:16,833 --> 01:55:17,843
He's bats.

1969
01:55:36,004 --> 01:55:38,404
Mary! Mary!

1970
01:55:41,226 --> 01:55:44,517
Tommy! Pete! Janie! Zuzu! 
Where are you?

1971
01:55:44,517 --> 01:55:47,286
They're not here, George. 
You have no children.

1972
01:55:47,286 --> 01:55:48,693
Where are they? 
What have you done with them?

1973
01:55:48,693 --> 01:55:50,995
All right, put up your hands. 
No fast moves.

1974
01:55:50,995 --> 01:55:52,580
Come on out here, both of you.

1975
01:55:52,580 --> 01:55:54,224
Bert! Thank heaven, you're here.

1976
01:55:54,224 --> 01:55:56,918
- Stand back!
- Bert, what's happened to this house?

1977
01:55:56,918 --> 01:55:58,445
Wh-Where's Mary? Where's my kids?

1978
01:55:58,445 --> 01:55:59,540
Watch him, Bert.

1979
01:55:59,540 --> 01:56:00,860
- Come on, come on.
- Bert, Ernie!

1980
01:56:00,860 --> 01:56:02,316
What's the matter with you two guys?

1981
01:56:02,316 --> 01:56:04,064
You — You — You were here 
on my wedding night.

1982
01:56:04,064 --> 01:56:07,021
You, both of you, stood out there on the 
porch and sung to us, don't you remember?

1983
01:56:07,021 --> 01:56:08,154
- Think I'd better be going.
- Look,

1984
01:56:08,154 --> 01:56:10,448
now why don't you be a good kid 
and we'll take you into a doctor.

1985
01:56:10,448 --> 01:56:12,251
- Everything's gonna be all right. Now ...
- Bert, now listen to me.

1986
01:56:12,251 --> 01:56:14,480
Ernie, will you take me over 
to my mother's house?

1987
01:56:14,480 --> 01:56:16,073
Bert! Listen! 
It's that fellow there.

1988
01:56:16,073 --> 01:56:18,276
He says he's an angel. 
He's tried to hypnotize me.

1989
01:56:18,276 --> 01:56:20,314
I hate to do this, fella, but ...

1990
01:56:21,983 --> 01:56:23,752
Run, George! Run, George!

1991
01:56:23,752 --> 01:56:27,570
Help! Joseph, help!

1992
01:56:27,570 --> 01:56:32,281
- Oh, shut up!
- Help, oh, Joseph, Joseph!

1993
01:56:37,933 --> 01:56:40,870
Where'd he go? Where'd he go? 
I had him right here.

1994
01:56:43,983 --> 01:56:45,081
I need a drink.

1995
01:56:45,996 --> 01:56:48,016
Well, which way'd they go? 
Help me find 'em.

1996
01:56:58,588 --> 01:56:59,854
Well?

1997
01:57:03,069 --> 01:57:04,134
Mother.

1998
01:57:06,156 --> 01:57:08,187
Mother? What do you want?

1999
01:57:09,324 --> 01:57:14,162
Mother, this is, this is George. 
I — I thought sure you'd remember me.

2000
01:57:14,162 --> 01:57:15,719
George who?

2001
01:57:15,719 --> 01:57:17,240
If you're looking for a room, 
there's no vacancy.

2002
01:57:17,240 --> 01:57:19,396
Oh, Mother, listen. Please help me.

2003
01:57:19,396 --> 01:57:20,670
Something terrible's happened to me.

2004
01:57:20,670 --> 01:57:23,460
I — I — I don't know what it is. 
Something's happened to everybody.

2005
01:57:23,460 --> 01:57:25,092
Please let me come in.

2006
01:57:25,092 --> 01:57:27,552
- Keep me here until I get over it.
- Get over what?

2007
01:57:27,552 --> 01:57:30,972
I don't take in strangers unless 
they're sent here by somebody I know.

2008
01:57:30,972 --> 01:57:34,739
What? 
Look, I know everybody you know.

2009
01:57:34,739 --> 01:57:36,916
What do you ... 
Your brother-in-law, Uncle Billy.

2010
01:57:36,916 --> 01:57:38,780
- You know him?
- Well, sure I do.

2011
01:57:38,780 --> 01:57:41,073
- When'd you see him last?
- Today over at his house.

2012
01:57:41,073 --> 01:57:42,191
That's a lie.

2013
01:57:42,191 --> 01:57:45,199
He's been in the insane asylum 
ever since he lost his business.

2014
01:57:45,199 --> 01:57:47,069
And if you ask me, 
that's where you belong.

2015
01:58:00,005 --> 01:58:02,112
Strange, isn't it?

2016
01:58:02,112 --> 01:58:05,582
Each man's life touches 
so many other lives ...

2017
01:58:05,582 --> 01:58:08,525
and when he isn't around he leaves 
an awful hole, doesn't he?

2018
01:58:08,525 --> 01:58:09,709
I've heard of things like this.

2019
01:58:09,709 --> 01:58:11,439
You've got me in some kind of a spell, 
or something.

2020
01:58:11,439 --> 01:58:13,867
Well, I'm going to get out of it. 
I'll get out of it.

2021
01:58:13,867 --> 01:58:15,939
I know how, too. 
I ...

2022
01:58:15,939 --> 01:58:19,505
The last man I talked to before all this 
stuff started happening to me was Martini.

2023
01:58:19,505 --> 01:58:20,505
You know where he lives?

2024
01:58:20,505 --> 01:58:22,708
Sure I know where he lives. 
He lives in Bailey Park.

2025
01:58:27,474 --> 01:58:29,909
Are you sure this is Bailey Park?

2026
01:58:29,909 --> 01:58:32,614
Oh, I'm not sure of anything anymore.

2027
01:58:32,614 --> 01:58:35,022
All I know is this should be Bailey Park.

2028
01:58:36,328 --> 01:58:37,974
But where are the houses?

2029
01:58:37,974 --> 01:58:39,664
You weren't here to build them.

2030
01:58:44,601 --> 01:58:46,502
Your brother, Harry Bailey,

2031
01:58:46,502 --> 01:58:49,630
broke through the ice 
and was drowned at the age of nine.

2032
01:58:49,630 --> 01:58:51,778
That's a lie. 
Harry Bailey went to war!

2033
01:58:51,778 --> 01:58:53,169
He got the Congressional 
Medal of Honor!

2034
01:58:53,169 --> 01:58:55,298
He saved the lives of every man 
on that transport.

2035
01:58:55,298 --> 01:58:57,455
Every man on that transport died.

2036
01:58:57,455 --> 01:59:01,337
Harry wasn't there to save them, 
because you weren't there to save Harry.

2037
01:59:12,874 --> 01:59:16,907
You see, George, you really 
had a wonderful life.

2038
01:59:16,907 --> 01:59:21,227
Don't you see what a mistake 
it would be to throw it away?

2039
01:59:21,635 --> 01:59:24,525
- Clarence ...
- Yes, George?

2040
01:59:24,525 --> 01:59:27,841
- Where's Mary?
- Oh, well, I — I — I can't do ...

2041
01:59:27,841 --> 01:59:29,201
I don't know how 
you know these things,

2042
01:59:29,201 --> 01:59:30,405
- but tell me, where is she?
- I ...

2043
01:59:30,405 --> 01:59:32,392
If you know where she is, 
tell me where my wife is.

2044
01:59:32,392 --> 01:59:33,662
I'm not supposed to tell.

2045
01:59:33,662 --> 01:59:35,529
Please, Clarence, 
tell me where she is.

2046
01:59:35,529 --> 01:59:37,872
- You're not going to like it, George.
- Where is she?

2047
01:59:37,872 --> 01:59:40,282
She's an old maid. 
She never married.

2048
01:59:40,282 --> 01:59:41,868
Where's Mary, where is she?

2049
01:59:41,868 --> 01:59:42,874
- She is ...
- Where is she?

2050
01:59:42,874 --> 01:59:45,803
She's just about 
to close up the library!

2051
01:59:48,863 --> 01:59:53,252
Aw, there must be some easier way 
for me to get my wings.

2052
02:00:04,567 --> 02:00:05,699
Mary!

2053
02:00:11,253 --> 02:00:12,340
Mary!

2054
02:00:14,971 --> 02:00:19,211
Mary, Mary, Mary ...

2055
02:00:19,211 --> 02:00:20,274
Mary, it's George.

2056
02:00:20,274 --> 02:00:21,764
Don't you know me? 
What's happened to us?

2057
02:00:21,764 --> 02:00:23,752
- I don't know you, let me go!
- Mary, please!

2058
02:00:23,752 --> 02:00:26,352
Oh, don't do this to me. 
Please, Mary, help me.

2059
02:00:26,352 --> 02:00:28,342
Where's our kids? I need you, Mary!

2060
02:00:29,221 --> 02:00:32,133
Help me, Mary! Mary ...

2061
02:00:32,133 --> 02:00:33,192
Let me go!

2062
02:00:35,256 --> 02:00:38,938
- Mary, don't run away!
- That man, stop him!

2063
02:00:38,938 --> 02:00:40,822
